# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: modula-3
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p01] The company produced many different product lines over its history.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p01] It is best known for the work in the minicomputer market starting in the early 1960s.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p01] The company produced a series of machines known as the PDP line, with the PDP-8 and PDP-11 being among the most successful minis in history.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p01] Their success was only surpassed by another DEC product, the late-1970s VAX "supermini" systems that were designed to replace the PDP-11.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p01] Although a number of competitors had successfully competed with Digital through the 1970s, the VAX cemented the company's place as a leading vendor in the computer space.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p01] As microcomputers improved in the late 1980s, especially with the introduction of RISC-based workstation machines, the performance niche of the minicomputer was rapidly eroded.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p01] By the early 1990s, the company was in turmoil as their mini sales collapsed and their attempts to address this by entering the high-end market with machines like the VAX 9000 were market failures.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p01] After several attempts to enter the workstation and file server market, the DEC Alpha product line began to make successful inroads in the mid-1990s, but was too late to save the company.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p01] DEC was acquired in June 1998 by Compaq in what was at that time the largest merger in the history of the computer industry.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p01] During the purchase, some parts of DEC were sold to other companies; the compiler business and the Hudson Fab were sold to Intel.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p01] At the time, Compaq was focused on the enterprise market and had recently purchased several other large vendors.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p01] DEC was a major player overseas where Compaq had less presence.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p01] However, Compaq had little idea what to do with its acquisitions, and soon found itself in financial difficulty of its own.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p01] Compaq was eventually bought by Hewlett-Packard (HP) in May 2002.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Ken Olsen and Harlan Anderson were two engineers who had been working at MIT Lincoln Laboratory on the lab's various computer projects.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The Lab is best known for their work on what would today be known as "interactivity", and their machines were among the first where operators had direct control over programs running in real-time.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] These had started in 1944 with the famed Whirlwind, which was originally developed to make a flight simulator for the US Navy, although this was never completed.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Instead, this effort evolved into the SAGE system for the US Air Force, which used large screens and light guns to allow operators to interact with radar data stored in the computer.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] When the Air Force project wound down, the Lab turned their attention to an effort to build a version of the Whirlwind using transistors in place of vacuum tubes.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] In order to test their new circuitry, they first built a small 18-bit machine known as TX-0, which first ran in 1956.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] When the TX-0 successfully proved the basic concepts, attention turned to a much larger system, the 36-bit TX-2 with a then-enormous 64 kWords of core memory.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Core was so expensive that parts of TX-0's memory were stripped for the TX-2, and what remained of the TX-0 was then given to MIT on permanent loan.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] At MIT, Ken Olsen and Harlan Anderson noticed something odd: students would line up for hours to get a turn to use the stripped-down TX-0, while largely ignoring a faster IBM machine that was also available.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The two decided that the draw of interactive computing was so strong that they felt there was a market for a small machine dedicated to this role, essentially a commercialized TX-0.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] They could sell this to users where the graphical output or real-time operation would be more important than outright performance.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Additionally, as the machine would cost much less than the larger systems then available, it would also be able to serve users that needed a lower-cost solution dedicated to a specific task, where a larger 36-bit machine would not be needed.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] In 1957, when the pair and Ken's brother Stan sought capital, they found that the American business community was hostile to investing in computer companies.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Many smaller computer companies had come and gone in the 1950s, wiped out when new technical developments rendered their platforms obsolete, and even large companies like RCA and General Electric were failing to make a profit in the market.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The only serious expression of interest came from Georges Doriot and his American Research and Development Corporation (AR&D).
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Worried that a new computer company would find it difficult to arrange further financing, Doriot suggested the fledgling company change its business plan to focus less on computers, and even change their name from "Digital Computer Corporation".
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The pair returned with an updated business plan that outlined two phases for the company's development.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] They would start by selling computer modules as stand-alone devices that could be purchased separately and wired together to produce a number of different digital systems for lab use.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Then, if these "digital modules" were able to build a self-sustaining business, the company would be free to use them to develop a complete computer in its Phase II.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] In early 1958, DEC shipped its first products, the "Digital Laboratory Module" line.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The Modules consisted of a number of individual electronic components and germanium transistors mounted to a circuit board, the actual circuits being based on those from the TX-2.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The Laboratory Modules were packaged in an extruded aluminum housing, intended to sit on an engineer's workbench, although a rack-mount bay was sold that held nine laboratory modules.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] They were then connected together using banana plug patch cords inserted at the front of the modules.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The Modules proved to be in high demand by other computer companies, who used them to build equipment to test their own systems.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Despite the recession of the late 1950s, the company sold $94,000 worth of these modules during 1958 alone (equivalent to $1,049,000 in 2025), turning a profit at the end of its first year.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The original Laboratory Modules were soon supplemented with the "Digital System Module" line, which were identical internally but packaged differently.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The Systems Modules were designed with all of the connections at the back of the module using 22-pin Amphenol connectors, and were attached to each other by plugging them into a backplane that could be mounted in a 19-inch rack.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The backplanes allowed 25 modules in a single 5-1/4 inch section of rack, and allowed the high densities needed to build a computer.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The original laboratory and system module lines were offered in 500 kilocycle, 5 megacycle and 10 megacycle versions.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] In all cases, the supply voltages were -15 and +10 volts, with logic levels of -3 volts (passive pull-down) and 0 volts (active pull-up).
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] DEC used the System Modules to build their "Memory Test" machine for testing core memory systems, selling about 50 of these pre-packaged units over the next eight years.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The PDP-1 and LINC computers were also built using System Modules (see below).
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Modules were part of DEC's product line into the 1970s, although they went through several evolutions during this time as technology changed.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The same circuits were then packaged as the first "R" (red) series "Flip-Chip" modules.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Later, other Flip-Chip module series provided additional speed, much higher logic density, and industrial I/O capabilities.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] DEC published extensive data about the modules in free catalogs that became very popular.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] With the company established and a successful product on the market, DEC turned its attention to the computer market once again as part of its planned "Phase II".
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] In August 1959, Ben Gurley started design of the company's first computer, the PDP-1.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] In keeping with Doriot's instructions, the name was an initialism for "Programmable Data Processor", leaving off the term "computer".
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] As Gurley put it, "We aren't building computers, we're building 'Programmable Data Processors'." The prototype was first shown publicly at the Joint Computer Conference in Boston in December 1959.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The first PDP-1 was delivered to Bolt, Beranek and Newman in November 1960, and formally accepted the next April.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] By the time production ended in 1969, 53 PDP-1s had been delivered.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The PDP-1 was supplied standard with 4096 words of core memory, 18-bits per word, and ran at a basic speed of 100,000 operations per second.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] It was constructed using many System Building Blocks that were packaged into several 19-inch racks.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The racks were themselves packaged into a single large mainframe case, with a hexagonal control panel containing switches and lights mounted to lie at table-top height at one end of the mainframe.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Above the control panel was the system's standard input/output solution, a punched tape reader and writer.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Most systems were purchased with two peripherals, the Type 30 vector graphics display, and a Soroban Engineering modified IBM Model B Electric typewriter that was used as a printer.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The Soroban system was notoriously unreliable, and often replaced with a modified Friden Flexowriter, which also contained its own punched tape system.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] A variety of more-expensive add-ons followed, including magnetic tape systems, punched card readers and punches, and faster punched tape and printer systems.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] When DEC introduced the PDP-1, they also mentioned larger machines at 24, 30 and 36 bits, based on the same design.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] During construction of the prototype PDP-1, some design work was carried out on a 24-bit PDP-2, and the 36-bit PDP-3.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Although the PDP-2 never proceeded beyond the initial design, the PDP-3 found some interest and was designed in full.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Only one PDP-3 appears to have been built, in 1960, by the CIA's Scientific Engineering Institute (SEI) in Waltham, Massachusetts.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] According to the limited information available, they used it to process radar cross section data for the Lockheed A-12 reconnaissance aircraft.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Gordon Bell remembered that it was being used in Oregon some time later, but could not recall who was using it.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The PDP-4 was similar to the PDP-1 and used a similar instruction set, but used slower memory and different packaging to lower the price.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Like the PDP-1, about 54 PDP-4s were eventually sold, most to a customer base similar to the original PDP-1.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] In 1964, DEC introduced its new Flip-Chip module design, and used it to re-implement the PDP-4 as the PDP-7.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The PDP-7 was introduced in December 1964, and about 120 were eventually produced.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] An upgrade to the Flip Chip led to the R series, which in turn led to the PDP-7A in 1965.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The PDP-7 is most famous as the machine for which the Unix operating system was originally written.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Unix ran only on DEC systems until the Interdata 8/32.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] A more dramatic upgrade to the PDP-1 series was introduced in August 1966, the PDP-9.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The PDP-9 was instruction-compatible with the PDP-4 and −7, but ran about twice as fast as the −7 and was intended to be used in larger deployments.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] At only $19,900 in 1968, the PDP-9 was a big seller, eventually selling 445 machines, more than all of the earlier models combined.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Even while the PDP-9 was being introduced, its replacement was being designed, and was introduced as 1969's PDP-15, which re-implemented the PDP-9 using integrated circuits in place of modules.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Much faster than the PDP-9 even in basic form, the PDP-15 also included a floating-point unit and a separate input/output processor for further performance gains.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Over 400 PDP-15's were ordered in the first eight months of production, and production eventually amounted to 790 examples in 12 basic models.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] However, by this time other machines in DEC's lineup could fill the same niche at even lower price points, and the PDP-15 would be the last of the 18-bit series.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] In 1962, Lincoln Laboratory used a selection of System Building Blocks to implement a small 12-bit machine, and attached it to a variety of analog-to-digital (A to D) input/output (I/O) devices that made it easy to interface with various analog lab equipment.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The LINC proved to attract intense interest in the scientific community, and has since been referred to as the first real minicomputer, a machine that was small and inexpensive enough to be dedicated to a single task even in a small lab.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Seeing the success of the LINC, in 1963 DEC took the basic logic design but stripped away the extensive A to D systems to produce the PDP-5.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The new machine, the first outside the PDP-1 mould, was introduced at WESCON on August 11, 1963.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] A 1964 ad expressed the main advantage of the PDP-5, "Now you can own the PDP-5 computer for what a core memory alone used to cost: $27,000".
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] 116 PDP-5s were produced until the lines were shut down in early 1967.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Like the PDP-1 before it, the PDP-5 inspired a series of newer models based on the same basic design that would go on to be more famous than its parent.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] On March 22, 1965, DEC introduced the PDP-8, which replaced the PDP-5's modules with the new R-series modules using Flip Chips.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The machine was re-packaged into a small tabletop case, which remains distinctive for its use of smoked plastic over the CPU which allowed one to easily see the logic modules plugged into the wire-wrapped backplane of the CPU.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Sold standard with 4 kWords of 12-bit core memory and a Teletype Model 33 ASR for basic input/output, the machine listed for only $18,000.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The PDP-8 is referred to as the first *real* minicomputer because of its sub-$25,000 price.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Sales were, unsurprisingly, very strong, and helped by the fact that several competitors had just entered the market with machines aimed directly at the PDP-5's market space, which the PDP-8 trounced.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] This gave the company two years of unrestricted leadership, and eventually 1450 "straight eight" machines were produced before it was replaced by newer implementations of the same basic design.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] DEC hit an even lower price-point with the PDP-8/S, the S for "serial".
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] As the name implies the /S used a serial arithmetic unit, which was much slower but reduced costs so much that the system sold for under $10,000.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] DEC then used the new PDP-8 design as the basis for a new LINC, the two-processor LINC-8.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The LINC-8 used one PDP-8 CPU and a separate LINC CPU, and included instructions to switch from one to the other.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] This allowed customers to run their existing LINC programs, or "upgrade" to the PDP-8, all in software.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Although not a huge seller, 142 LINC-8s were sold starting at $38,500.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Like the original LINC to PDP-5 evolution, the LINC-8 was then modified into the single-processor PDP-12, adding another 1000 machines to the 12-bit family.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Newer circuitry designs led to the PDP-8/I and PDP-8/L in 1968.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] In 1975, one year after an agreement between DEC and Intersil, the Intersil 6100 chip was launched, effectively a PDP-8 on a chip.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] This was a way to allow PDP-8 software to be run even after the official end-of-life announcement for the DEC PDP-8 product line.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] While the PDP-5 introduced a lower-cost line, 1963's PDP-6 was intended to take DEC into the mainframe market with a 36-bit machine.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] However, the PDP-6 proved to be a "hard sell" with customers, as it offered few obvious advantages over similar machines from the better-established vendors like IBM or Honeywell, in spite of its low cost around $300,000.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Only 23 were sold, or 26 depending on the source, and unlike other models the low sales meant the PDP-6 was not improved with successor versions.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] However, the PDP-6 is historically important as the platform that introduced "Monitor", an early time-sharing operating system that would evolve into the widely used TOPS-10.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] When newer Flip Chip packaging allowed the PDP-6 to be re-implemented at a much lower cost, DEC took the opportunity to refine their 36-bit design, introducing the PDP-10 in 1968.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The PDP-10 was as much a success as the PDP-6 was a commercial failure; about 700 mainframe PDP-10s were sold before production ended in 1984.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The PDP-10 was widely used in university settings, and thus was the basis of many advances in computing and operating system design during the 1970s.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Unified product line upgrades produced the compatible DECSYSTEM-20, along with a TOPS-20 operating system that included virtual memory support.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The Jupiter Project was supposed to continue the mainframe product line into the future by using gate arrays with an innovative Air Mover Cooling System, coupled with a built-in floating point processing engine called "FBOX".
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The design was intended for a top tier scientific computing niche, yet the critical performance measurement was based upon COBOL compilation which did not fully utilize the primary design features of Jupiter technology.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] When the Jupiter Project was cancelled in 1983, some of the engineers adapted aspects of the 36-bit design into a forthcoming 32-bit design, releasing the high-end VAX8600 in 1985.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] DEC's successful entry into the computer market took place during a fundamental shift in the underlying organization of the machines from word lengths based on 6-bit characters to those based on 8-bit words needed to support ASCII.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] DEC began studies of such a machine, the PDP-X, but Ken Olsen did not support it as he could not see how it offered anything their existing 12-bit or 18-bit machines didn't.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] This led the leaders of the PDP-X project to leave DEC and start Data General, whose 16-bit Data General Nova was released in 1969 and was a huge success.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The success of the Nova finally prompted DEC to take the switch seriously, and they began a crash program to introduce a 16-bit machine of their own.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The new system was designed primarily by Harold McFarland, Gordon Bell, Roger Cady, and others.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The project was able to leap forward in design with the arrival of Harold McFarland, who had been researching 16-bit designs at Carnegie Mellon University.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] One of his simpler designs became the basis for the new design, although when they first viewed the proposal, management was not impressed and almost cancelled it.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The result was the PDP-11, released in 1970.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] It differed from earlier designs considerably.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] In particular, the new design did not include many of the addressing modes that were intended to make programs smaller in memory, a technique that was widely used on other DEC machines and CISC designs in general.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] This would mean the machine would spend more time accessing memory, which would slow it down.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] However, the machine also extended the idea of multiple "General Purpose Registers" (GPRs), which gave the programmer flexibility to use these high-speed memory caches as they needed, potentially addressing the performance issues.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] A major advance in the PDP-11 design was DEC's Unibus, which supported all peripherals through memory mapping.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] This allowed a new device to be added easily, generally only requiring plugging a hardware interface board into the backplane and possibly adding a jumper to the wire wrapped backplane, and then installing software that read and wrote to the mapped memory to control it.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The relative ease of interfacing spawned a huge market of third party add-ons for the PDP-11, which made the machine even more useful.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The combination of architectural innovations proved superior to competitors and the "11" architecture was soon the industry leader, propelling DEC back to a strong market position.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The design was later expanded to allow paged physical memory and memory protection features, useful for multitasking and time-sharing.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Some models supported separate instruction and data spaces for an effective virtual address size of 128 KB within a physical address size of up to 4 MB.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Smaller PDP-11s, implemented as single-chip CPUs, continued to be produced until 1996, by which time over 600,000 had been sold.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The PDP-11 supported several operating systems, including Bell Labs' new Unix operating system as well as DEC's DOS-11, RSX-11, IAS, RT-11, DSM-11, and RSTS/E.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Many early PDP-11 applications were developed using standalone paper-tape utilities.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] DOS-11 was the PDP-11's first disk operating system, but was soon supplanted by more capable systems.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] RSX provided a general-purpose multitasking environment and supported a wide variety of programming languages.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] IAS was a time-sharing version of RSX-11D.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Both RSTS and Unix were time-sharing systems available to educational institutions at little or no cost, and these PDP-11 systems were destined to be the "sandbox" for a rising generation of engineers and computer scientists.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Large numbers of PDP-11/70s were deployed in telecommunications and industrial control applications.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] AT&T Corporation became DEC's largest customer.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] RT-11 provided a practical real-time operating system in minimal memory, allowing the PDP-11 to continue DEC's critical role as a computer supplier for embedded systems.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Historically, RT-11 also served as the inspiration for many microcomputer OS's, as these were generally being written by programmers who cut their teeth on one of the many PDP-11 models.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] For example, CP/M used a command syntax similar to RT-11's, and even retained the awkward PIP program used to copy data from one computer device to another.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] As another historical footnote, DEC's use of "/" for "switches" (command-line options) would lead to the adoption of "\" for pathnames in MS-DOS and Microsoft Windows as opposed to "/" in Unix.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The evolution of the PDP-11 followed earlier systems, eventually including a single-user deskside personal computer form, the MicroPDP-11.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] In total, around 600,000 PDP-11s of all models were sold, and a wide variety of third-party peripheral vendors had also entered the computer product ecosystem.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] It was even sold in kit form as the Heathkit H11, although it proved too expensive for Heathkit's traditional hobbyist market.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The introduction of semiconductor memory in the early 1970s, and especially dynamic RAM shortly thereafter, led to dramatic reductions in the price of memory as the effects of Moore's Law were felt.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Within years, it was common to equip a machine with all the memory it could address, typically 64 KB on 16-bit machines.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] This led vendors to introduce new designs with the ability to address more memory, often by extending the address format to 18 or 24 bits in machines that were otherwise similar to their earlier 16-bit designs.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] In contrast, DEC decided to make a more radical departure.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] In 1976, they began the design of a machine whose entire architecture was expanded from the 16-bit PDP-11 to a new 32-bit basis.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] This would allow the addressing of very large memories, which were to be controlled by a new virtual memory system, and would also improve performance by processing twice as much data at a time.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The system would, however, maintain compatibility with the PDP-11, by operating in a second mode that sent its 16-bit words into the 32-bit internals, while mapping the PDP-11's 16-bit memory space into the larger virtual 32-bit space.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The result was the VAX architecture, where VAX stands for Virtual Address eXtension (from 16 to 32 bits).
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The first computer to use a VAX CPU was the VAX-11/780, announced in October 1977, which DEC referred to as a *superminicomputer*.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Although it was not the first 32-bit minicomputer, the VAX-11/780's combination of features, price, and marketing almost immediately propelled it to a leadership position in the market after it was released in 1978.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] VAX systems were so successful that in 1983, DEC canceled its Jupiter project, which had been intended to build a successor to the PDP-10 mainframe, and instead focused on promoting the VAX as the single computer architecture for the company.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Supporting the VAX's success was the VT52, one of the most successful smart terminals.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Building on earlier less successful models, the VT05 and VT50, the VT52 was the first terminal that did everything one might want in a single inexpensive chassis.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The VT52 was followed by the even more successful VT100 and its follow-ons, making DEC one of the largest terminal vendors in the industry.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] This was supported by a line of inexpensive computer printers, the DECwriter line.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] With the VT and DECwriter series, DEC could now offer a complete top-to-bottom system from computer to all peripherals, which formerly required collecting the required devices from different suppliers.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The VAX processor architecture and family of systems evolved and expanded through several generations during the 1980s, culminating in the NVAX microprocessor implementation and VAX 7000/10000 series in the early 1990s.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] When a DEC research group demonstrated two prototype microcomputers in 1974—before the debut of the MITS Altair—Olsen chose to not proceed with the project.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The company similarly rejected another personal computer proposal in 1977.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] At the time these systems were of limited utility, and Olsen famously derided them in 1977, stating "There is no reason for any individual to have a computer in his home." Unsurprisingly, DEC did not put much effort into the microcomputer area in the early days of the market.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] In 1977, the Heathkit H11 was announced; a PDP-11 in kit form.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] At the beginning of the 1980s, DEC built the VT180 (codenamed "Robin"), which was a VT100 terminal with an added Z80-based microcomputer running CP/M, but this product was initially available only to DEC employees.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] It was only after IBM had successfully launched the IBM PC in 1981 that DEC responded with their own systems.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] In 1982, DEC introduced not one, but three incompatible machines which were each tied to different proprietary architectures.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The first, the DEC Professional, was based on the PDP-11/23 (and later, the 11/73) running the RSX-11M+ derived, but menu-driven, P/OS ("Professional Operating System").
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] This DEC machine easily outperformed the PC, but was more expensive than, and completely incompatible with IBM PC hardware and software, offering far fewer options for customizing a system.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Unlike CP/M and DOS microcomputers, every copy of every program for the Professional had to be provided with a unique key for the particular machine and CPU for which it was bought.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] At that time this was mainstream policy, because most computer software was either bought from the company that built the computer or custom-constructed for one client.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] However, the emerging third-party software industry disregarded the PDP-11/Professional line and concentrated on other microcomputers where distribution was easier.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] At DEC itself, creating better programs for the Professional was not a priority, perhaps from fear of cannibalizing the PDP-11 line.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] As a result, the Professional was a superior machine, running inferior software.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] In addition, a new user would have to learn an awkward, slow, and inflexible menu-based user interface which appeared to be radically different from PC DOS or CP/M, which were more commonly used on the 8080- and 8088-based microcomputers of the time.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] A second offering, the DECmate II was the latest version of the PDP-8-based word processors, but not really suited to general computing, nor competitive with Wang Laboratories' popular word processing equipment.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The most popular early DEC microcomputer was the dual-processor (Z80 and 8088) Rainbow 100, which ran the 8-bit CP/M operating system on the Z80 and the 16-bit CP/M-86 operating system on the Intel 8088 processor.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] It could also run a UNIX System III implementation called VENIX.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Applications from standard CP/M could be re-compiled for the Rainbow, but by this time users were expecting custom-built (pre-compiled binary) applications such as Lotus 1-2-3, which was eventually ported along with MS-DOS 2.0 and introduced in late 1983.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Although the Rainbow generated some press, it was unsuccessful due to its high price and lack of marketing and sales support.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] By late 1983 IBM was outselling DEC's personal computers by more than ten to one.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] A further system was introduced in 1986 as the VAXmate, which included Microsoft Windows 1.0 and used VAX/VMS-based file and print servers along with integration into DEC's own DECnet-family, providing LAN/WAN connection from PC to mainframe or supermini.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The VAXmate replaced the Rainbow, and in its standard form was the first widely marketed diskless workstation.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] In 1984, DEC launched its first 10 Mbit/s Ethernet.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Ethernet allowed scalable networking, and VAXcluster allowed scalable computing.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Combined with DECnet and Ethernet-based terminal servers (LAT), DEC had produced a networked storage architecture which allowed them to compete directly with IBM.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Ethernet replaced Token Ring, and went on to become the dominant networking model in use today.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] In September 1985, DEC became the fifth company to register a .com domain name (dec.com).
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Along with the hardware and protocols, DEC also introduced the VAXcluster concept, which allowed several VAX machines to be tied together into a single larger storage system.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] VAXclusters allowed a DEC-based company to scale their services by adding new machines to the cluster at any time, as opposed to buying a faster machine and using that to replace a slower one.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The flexibility this offered was compelling, and allowed DEC to attack high-end markets formerly out of their reach.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The PDP-11 and VAX lines continued to sell in record numbers.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Better yet, DEC was competing very well against the market leader, IBM, taking an estimated $2 billion away from them in the mid-1980s.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] In 1986, DEC's profits rose 38% when the rest of the computer industry experienced a downturn, and by 1987 the company was threatening IBM's number one position in the computer industry.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Not long thereafter came IBM's "VAX killer" offerings, at a time when DEC had twice the sales of IBM in the mid-range computer market.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] At its peak, DEC was the second-largest computer company in the world, with over 100,000 employees.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] It was during this time that the company branched out development into a wide variety of projects that were far from its core business in computer equipment.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The company invested heavily in custom software.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] In the 1970s and earlier, most software was custom-written to serve a specific task, but by the 1980s the introduction of relational databases and similar systems allowed powerful software to be built in a modular fashion, potentially saving enormous amounts of development time.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Software companies like Oracle became the new darlings of the industry, and DEC started their own efforts in every "hot" niche, in some cases several projects for the same niche.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Some of these products competed with DEC's own partners, notably Rdb which competed with Oracle's products on the VAX, part of a major partnership only a few years earlier.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Although many of these products were well designed, most of them were DEC-only or DEC-centric, and customers frequently ignored them and used third-party products instead.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] This problem was further exacerbated by Olsen's aversion to traditional advertising and his belief that well-engineered products would sell themselves.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Hundreds of millions of dollars were spent on these projects, at the same time that workstations using RISC microprocessors were starting to approach VAX CPUs in performance.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] As microprocessors continued to improve in the 1980s, it soon became clear that the next generation would offer performance and features equal to the best of DECs low-end minicomputer lineup.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Worse, the Berkeley RISC and Stanford MIPS designs were aiming to introduce 32-bit designs that would outperform the fastest members of the VAX family, DEC's cash cow.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The company recognized that RISC offered at least twice as many MIPS per cost as VAX, but funded so many competing projects in reaction during the 1980s that it lost control of its strategy until the early 1990s.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Constrained by the huge success of their VAX and VMS products, which followed the proprietary model, the company was very late to respond to these threats.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] In the early 1990s, DEC found its sales faltering and its first layoffs followed.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The company that created the minicomputer, a dominant networking technology, and arguably the first computers for personal use, had abandoned the "low end" market, whose dominance with the PDP-8 had built the company in a previous generation.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Decisions about what to do about this threat led to infighting within the company that seriously delayed their responses.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] One group suggested that every possible development in the industry be poured into the construction of a new VAX family that would leapfrog the performance of the existing machines.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] This would limit the market erosion in the top-end segment, where profit margins were maximized and DEC could continue to survive as a minicomputer vendor.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] This line of thought led, eventually, to the VAX 9000 series, which were plagued with problems when they were first introduced in October 1989, already two years late.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The problems took so long to work out, and the prices of the systems were so high, that DEC was never able to make the line the success they hoped.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Others within the company felt that the proper response was to introduce their own RISC designs and use those to build new machines.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] However, there was little official support for these efforts, and no less than four separate small projects ran in parallel at various labs around the US.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Eventually these were gathered into the PRISM project, which delivered a credible 32-bit design with some unique features allowing it to serve as the basis of a new VAX implementation.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Infighting with teams dedicated to DEC's big iron made funding difficult, and the design was not finalized until April 1988, and then cancelled shortly thereafter.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The PRISM project was accompanied by the MICA project, which intended to consolidate VMS and ULTRIX into a single operating system.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Another group concluded that new workstations like those from Sun Microsystems and Silicon Graphics would take away a large part of DEC's existing customer base before the new VAX systems could address the issues, and that the company needed its own Unix workstation as soon as possible.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Fed up with slow progress on both the RISC and VAX fronts, a group in Palo Alto started a skunkworks project to introduce their own systems.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Selecting the MIPS processor, which was widely available, introducing the new DECstation series with the model 3100 on January 11, 1989.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] These systems would see some success in the market, but were later displaced by similar models running the Alpha.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The press described DECstation as a defensive product with which DEC would capture some of the inevitable migration of VAX customers to RISC, even as it and comparable products from rivals would greatly increase the migration.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Eventually, in 1992, DEC launched the DECchip 21064 processor, the first implementation of their Alpha instruction set architecture, initially named Alpha AXP; the "AXP" was a "non-acronym" and was later dropped.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] This was a 64-bit RISC architecture as opposed to the 32-bit CISC architecture used in the VAX.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] It is one of the first "pure" 64-bit microprocessor architectures and implementations rather than an extension of an earlier 32-bit architecture.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The Alpha offered class-leading performance at its launch and was used in the massively-parallel Cray T3D.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Subsequent variants continued that performance trend into the 2000s, along with the Alpha-derived Pentium Pro, II, and III CPUs.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] An AlphaServer SC45 supercomputer was still ranked No.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Alpha-based computers comprising the DEC AXP series, later the AlphaStation, and AlphaServer series respectively superseded both the VAX and MIPS architecture in DEC's product lines.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] They supported OpenVMS, DEC OSF/1 AXP (later known as Digital Unix or Tru64 UNIX) and Microsoft's then-new operating system, Windows NT, an operating system made possible by ex-Digital Equipment Corporation engineers.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] In 1998, following the takeover by Compaq Computer Corporation, a decision was made that Microsoft would no longer support and develop Windows NT for the Alpha series computers, a decision that was seen as the beginning of the end for the Alpha series computers.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] In the mid-1990s, Digital Semiconductor collaborated with ARM Limited to produce the StrongARM microprocessor.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] This was based in part on ARM7 and in part on DEC technologies like Alpha, and was targeted at embedded systems and portable devices.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] It was highly compatible with the ARMv4 architecture and was very successful, competing effectively against rivals such as the SuperH and MIPS architectures in the personal digital assistant market.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Microsoft subsequently dropped support for these other architectures in their Pocket PC platform.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] In 1997, as part of a lawsuit settlement, the StrongARM intellectual property was sold to Intel.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] They continued to produce StrongARM, as well as developing it into the XScale architecture.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Intel subsequently sold this business to Marvell Technology Group in 2006.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] At its peak in the late 1980s, DEC had $14 billion in sales and ranked among the most profitable companies in the US.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] With its strong staff of engineers, DEC was expected to usher in the age of personal computers, but the commonly misunderstood belief then argued by the board to its shareholders was that Mr.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Olsen was openly skeptical of the desktop machines, stating "the personal computer will fall flat on its face in business", and regarding them as "toys" used for playing video games.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] This was made in 1977 about what could be more characterised as home automation devices.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] By 1991 DEC was still unable to sell PCs to its customers, which standardized on other vendors like Compaq and HP.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The board forced Olsen to resign as president in July 1992 after two years of losses in operating income.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] He was replaced by Robert Palmer as the company's president.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] DEC's board of directors also granted Palmer the title of chief executive officer ("CEO"), a title that had never been used during DEC's 35-year existence.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Palmer had joined DEC in 1985 to run Semiconductor Engineering and Manufacturing.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] His relentless campaign to be CEO, and success with the Alpha microprocessor family, made him a candidate to succeed Olsen.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] At the same time a more modern logo was designed.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Alpha was so important to the company that *PC Week* wrote of its introduction, "Beleaguered Digital Equipment Corp. will begin this week what may be the fight of its life".
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] DEC was, the magazine said, "undergoing wrenching organization change, including thousands of layoffs".
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] By then DEC was stating when marketing DECpc that while "the Digital of yesterday was not known for competitive prices, this new line of PC offerings is competitive in features and price", and bragging about its more than $1 billion in annual mail order sales.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Palmer restructured DEC into nine business units that reported directly to him.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Nonetheless, DEC continued to suffer record losses, including a loss of $260.5 million for the quarter that ended on September 30, 1992.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] It reported $2.8 billion in losses for its fiscal year 1992.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] January 5, 1993, saw the retirement of John F.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Smith as senior vice president of operations, the second in command at DEC, and his position was not filled.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] A 35-year company veteran, he had joined DEC in 1958 as the company's 12th employee, passing up a chance to work for Bell Laboratories in New Jersey to work for DEC.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Smith rose to become one of the three senior vice presidents in 1987 and was widely considered among the potential successors to Ken Olsen, especially when Smith was appointed chief operating officer in 1991.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Smith became a corporate spokesman on financial issues, and had filled in at trouble spots for which Olsen ordered more attention.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Smith was passed over in favor of Palmer when Olsen was forced to resign in July 1992, though Smith stayed on for a time to help turn around the struggling company.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] In June 1993, Palmer and several of his top lieutenants presented their reorganization plans to applause from the board of directors, and several weeks later DEC reported its first profitable quarter in several years.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] However, on April 15, 1994, DEC reported a loss of $183 million—three to four times higher than the loss many people on Wall Street had predicted (compared with a loss of $30 million in the comparable period a year earlier), causing the stock price on the NYSE to plunge $5.875 to $23, a 20% drop.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The losses at that point totaled $339 million for the current fiscal year.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] When Olsen resigned, an industry analyst said "If Alpha fails, DEC is dead".
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Market acceptance of Alpha computers and chips was slower than the company had hoped, even though Alpha's sales for the quarter estimated at $275 million were up significantly from $165 million in the December quarter.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] DEC had also made a strong push into personal computers and workstations, which had even lower margins than Alpha computers and chips.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Also, DEC was playing catchup with its own Unix offerings for client-server networks, as it long emphasized its own VMS software, while corporate computer users based their client-server networks on the industry-standard Unix software (of which Hewlett-Packard was one of the market leaders).
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] During the profitable years up until the early 1990s, DEC was a company that boasted that it never had a general layoff.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Following the 1992 economic downturn, layoffs became regular events as the company continually downsized to try to stay afloat.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Through 1997, DEC began discussions with Compaq on a possible merger.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Several years earlier, Compaq had considered a bid for DEC but became seriously interested only after DEC's major divestments and refocusing on the Internet in 1997.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] At that time, Compaq was making strong moves into the enterprise market, and DEC's multivendor global services organization and customer support centers offered a real opportunity to expand their support and sales worldwide.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Compaq was not interested in a number of DEC's product lines, which led to the series of sell-offs.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Notable among these was DEC's Hudson Fab, which made most of their custom chips, a market that made little sense to Compaq's "industry standard" marketing.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] DEC had previously sold its semiconductor plant in South Queensferry to Motorola in 1995, with an understanding that Motorola would continue to produce Alpha processors at the facility, along with continuing a two-year foundry agreement with AMD to continue producing the Am486 processor.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] This led to an interesting solution to the problem of selling off the division for a reasonable profit.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] In May 1997, DEC sued Intel for allegedly infringing on its Alpha patents in designing the original Pentium, Pentium Pro, and Pentium II chips.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] As part of a settlement, much of DEC's chip design and fabrication business was sold to Intel.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] This included DEC's StrongARM implementation of the ARM computer architecture, which Intel marketed as the XScale processors commonly used in Pocket PCs.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The core of Digital Semiconductor, the Alpha microprocessor group, remained with DEC, while the associated office buildings went to Intel as part of the Hudson fab.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] On January 26, 1998, what remained of the company was sold to Compaq in what was the largest merger up to that time in the computer industry.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] At the time of Compaq's acquisition announcement, DEC had a total of 53,500 employees, down from a peak of 130,000 in the 1980s, but it still employed about 65% more people than Compaq to produce about half the volume of sales revenues.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] After the merger closed, Compaq moved aggressively to reduce DEC's high selling, general, and administrative (SG&A) costs (equal to 24% of total 1997 revenues) and bring them more in line with Compaq's SG&A expense ratio of 12% of revenues.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Compaq used the acquisition to move into enterprise services and compete with IBM, and by 2001 services made up over 20% of Compaq's revenues, largely due to the DEC employees inherited from the merger.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] DEC's own PC manufacturing was discontinued after the merger closed.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Compaq struggled as a result of the merger with DEC, and was acquired by Hewlett-Packard in 2002.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Compaq, and later HP, continued to sell many of the former DEC products but re-branded with their own logos.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] For example, HP now sells what were formerly DEC's StorageWorks disk/tape products, as a result of the Compaq acquisition.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] The Digital logo was used up until 2004, even after the company ceased to exist, as the logo of Digital GlobalSoft, an IT services company in India (which was a 51% subsidiary of Compaq).
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Digital GlobalSoft was later renamed "HP GlobalSoft" (also known as the "HP Global Delivery India Center" or HP GDIC), and no longer uses the Digital logo.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p02] Compaq transferred the DEC company archives to the Computer History Museum in 2004.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p03] DEC's Research Laboratories (or Research Labs, as they were commonly known) conducted DEC's corporate research.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p03] Some of them were continued in operation by Compaq and are still operated by Hewlett-Packard.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p03] Grace Hopper worked for Digital Equipment Corporation as a consultant after her retirement from the United States Navy.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p03] Some of the work of the Research Labs was published in the *Digital Technical Journal*, which was in published from 1985 until 1998.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p03] At least some of the research reports are available online.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p03] As of 2012, decades-old hardware (including PDP-11, VAX, and AlphaServer) is being emulated to allow legacy software to run on modern hardware; funding for this is planned to last at least until 2030.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p03] DEC supported the ANSI standards, especially the ASCII character set, which survives in Unicode and the ISO 8859 character set family.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p03] DEC's own Multinational Character Set also had a large influence on ISO 8859-1 (Latin-1) and, by extension, Unicode.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p03] One of the most unusual peripherals produced for the PDP-10 was the DECtape.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p03] The DECtape was a length of special 3/4-inch wide magnetic tape wound on 5-inch reels.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p03] The recording format was a highly reliable redundant 10-track design using fixed-length numbered data "blocks" organized into a standard file structure, including a directory.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p03] Files could be written, read, changed, and deleted on a DECtape as though it were a disk drive.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p03] For greater efficiency, the DECtape drive could read and write to a DECtape in both directions.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p03] In fact, some PDP-10 systems had no disks at all, using DECtapes alone for their primary data storage.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p03] The DECtape was also widely used on other PDP models, since it was much easier to use than hand-loading multiple paper tapes.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p03] Primitive early time-sharing systems could use DECtapes as system devices and swapping devices.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p03] Although superior to paper tape, DECtapes were relatively slow, and were supplanted once reliable disk drives became affordable.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p03] DEC was both a manufacturer and a buyer of magnetic disk storage, offering more than 100 different models of hard disk drive (HDD) and floppy disk drive (FDD) during its existence.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p03] In the 1970s, it was the single largest OEM purchaser of HDDs, procuring from Diablo, Control Data Corporation, Information Storage Systems, and Memorex, among others.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p03] DEC's first internally developed HDD was the RS08, a 256 kWord fixed-head contact-start-stop drive using plated media; it shipped in 1969.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p03] Beginning in the 1970s, DEC moved first its HDD manufacturing and then its mass storage development labs to Colorado Springs.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p03] DEC pioneered a number of HDD technologies, including sampled data servos (RL01, 1977) and serial HDD interfaces (Standard Disk Interconnect, 1983).
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p03] The last internally developed disk drive family (RA9x series) used plated media, departing from the HDD industry trend to carbon overcoated sputtered media.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p03] DEC designated a $400 million investment to bring this product line into production.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p03] The RA92 (1.5 GB) was introduced in 1992, using a 14-inch platter.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p03] DEC purchased its FDDs from OEMs such as Shugart Associates, Toshiba, and Sony.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p03] The way the 400 KB DEC standard RX50 floppy disk drive supported DEC's initial offerings seemed to encapsulate their approach to the personal computer market.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p03] Although the mechanical drive hardware was nearly identical to other 5 1⁄4" floppy disk drives available on competing systems, DEC sought to differentiate their product by using a proprietary disk format for the data written on the disk.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p03] The DEC format had a higher capacity for data, but the RX50 drives were incompatible with other PC floppy drives.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p03] This required DEC owners to buy higher-priced, specially formatted floppy media, which was harder to obtain through standard distribution channels.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p03] DEC attempted to enforce exclusive control over its floppy media sales by copyrighting its proprietary disk format, and requiring a negotiated license agreement and royalty payments from anybody selling compatible media.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p03] The proprietary data format meant that RX50 floppies were not interchangeable with other PC floppies, further isolating DEC products from the developing de facto standard PC market.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p03] Hardware hackers and DEC enthusiasts eventually reverse-engineered the RX50 format, but the damage had already been done, in terms of market confusion and isolation.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p03] The video-on-demand project at DEC started in 1992, following Ken Olsen's retirement.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p03] At the time the company was rapidly downsizing under Robert Palmer, and it was difficult to gain funding for any new project.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p03] DEC's Interactive Video Information Server architecture gained traction and excelled over those of other companies, in that it was highly scalable, using a gateway to set up interactive video delivery sessions on large numbers of video and information servers.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p03] Initially high-end VAXes were used, then Alphas.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p03] In 1993 the DEC video-on-demand design team developed a system with a session gateway between the users and a large number of servers.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p03] The system was successful in winning video-on-demand trials at US West and other companies.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p03] Shortly after the first patent was filed, the session gateway and session gateway and server concept was released to the public domain and proposed in the early Digital Audio Visual Council and MPEG-2 international standards deliberations, with approximately 50 companies attending.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p03] The architecture was accepted and voted into the final standards.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p03] In 1993 the design team further developed a media client buffer design that used receive-side buffering for media streaming with read and write pointers.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p03] This enabled VCR-like features pause, fast forward, and rewind to be performed at the user's device, e.g. cellphone or laptop, even before the full video was downloaded.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p03] This enabled more servers to be allocated to the system, as these features did not always have to be performed at the servers.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p03] In 1995 the system, renamed the "Video and Interactive Information Server", was upgraded with the capability of providing exponentially more video and information access using a hierarchy of session gateways, session gateway proxies, and servers.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p03] With this 1995 Video and Interactive Information Server design, 333,000 streams were provided by US West to set-top box users, and was used by Adlink to distribute advertising to over two million subscribers.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p03] The DEC video-on-demand patents portfolio has been cited over 350 times.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p03] A Google search in 2025 asking performance improvement of computers from 1995 (the date of this invention) to 2025 yielded 100-1000x performance increase, depending on the usage.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p03] Assuming the conservative value of 100x performance, the DEC Video and Interactive Information Server would be able to supply 33 million streams in 2025.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p03] The scalability feature allowed it to win contracts for many of the trials in the 1993-97 timeframe, since the system could theoretically accommodate an extremely large amount of video streams and other non-video content.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p03] The design was proposed and incorporated into the MPEG-2 international standard (finalized in 1995).
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p03] Its object-oriented interface became the mandatory user-to user core interface in DSM-CC, widely used in video stream and file delivery for MPEG-2 compliant systems, and was carried forward to MPEG-3 compliant systems.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p03] Originally the users' group was called DECUS (Digital Equipment Computer User Society) during the 1960s to 1990s.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p03] When Compaq acquired DEC in 1998, the users group was renamed CUO, the Compaq Users' Organisation.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p03] When HP acquired Compaq in 2002, CUO became HP-Interex, although there are still DECUS groups in several countries.
[src:modula-3/digital-equipment-corporation-p03] In the United States, the organization is represented by the Encompass organization; currently Connect.
[src:modula-3/exception-handling] In computing and computer programming, **exception handling** is the process of responding to the occurrence of *exceptions* – anomalous or exceptional conditions requiring special processing – during the execution of a program.
[src:modula-3/exception-handling] In general, an exception breaks the normal flow of execution and executes a pre-registered *exception handler*; the details of how this is done depend on whether it is a hardware or software exception and how the software exception is implemented.
[src:modula-3/exception-handling] Exceptions are defined by different layers of a computer system, and the typical layers are CPU-defined interrupts, operating system (OS)-defined signals, and programming language-defined exceptions.
[src:modula-3/exception-handling] Each layer requires different ways of exception handling although they may be interrelated, e.g. a CPU interrupt could be turned into an OS signal.
[src:modula-3/exception-handling] Some exceptions, especially hardware ones, may be handled so gracefully that execution can resume where it was interrupted.
[src:modula-3/exception-handling] The definition of an exception is based on the observation that each procedure has a precondition, a set of circumstances for which it will terminate "normally".
[src:modula-3/exception-handling] An exception handling mechanism allows the procedure to *raise an exception* if this precondition is violated, for example if the procedure has been called on an abnormal set of arguments.
[src:modula-3/exception-handling] The exception handling mechanism then *handles* the exception.
[src:modula-3/exception-handling] The precondition, and the definition of exception, is subjective.
[src:modula-3/exception-handling] The set of "normal" circumstances is defined entirely by the programmer, e.g. the programmer may deem division by zero to be undefined, hence an exception, or devise some behavior such as returning zero or a special "ZERO DIVIDE" value (circumventing the need for exceptions).
[src:modula-3/exception-handling] Social pressure is a major influence on the scope of exceptions and use of exception-handling mechanisms, i.e.
[src:modula-3/exception-handling] "examples of use, typically found in core libraries, and code examples in technical books, magazine articles, and online discussion forums, and in an organization’s code standards".
[src:modula-3/exception-handling] Exception handling solves the semipredicate problem, in that the mechanism distinguishes normal return values from erroneous ones.
[src:modula-3/exception-handling] In languages without built-in exception handling such as C, routines would need to signal the error in some other way, such as the common return code and errno pattern.
[src:modula-3/exception-handling] Taking a broad view, errors can be considered to be a proper subset of exceptions, and explicit error mechanisms such as errno can be considered (verbose) forms of exception handling.
[src:modula-3/exception-handling] The term "exception" is preferred to "error" because it does not imply that anything is wrong - a condition viewed as an error by one procedure or programmer may not be viewed that way by another.
[src:modula-3/exception-handling] The term "exception" may be misleading because its connotation of "anomaly" indicates that raising an exception is abnormal or unusual, when in fact raising the exception may be a normal and usual situation in the program.
[src:modula-3/exception-handling] For example, suppose a lookup function for an associative array throws an exception if the key has no value associated.
[src:modula-3/exception-handling] Depending on context, this "key absent" exception may occur much more often than a successful lookup.
[src:modula-3/exception-handling] The first hardware exception handling was found in the UNIVAC I from 1951.
[src:modula-3/exception-handling] Arithmetic overflow executed two instructions at address 0 which could transfer control or fix up the result.
[src:modula-3/exception-handling] Software exception handling developed in the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:modula-3/exception-handling] Exception handling was subsequently widely adopted by many programming languages from the 1980s onward.
[src:modula-3/exception-handling] There is no clear consensus as to the exact meaning of an exception with respect to hardware.
[src:modula-3/exception-handling] From the implementation point of view, it is handled identically to an interrupt: the processor halts execution of the current program, looks up the interrupt handler in the interrupt vector table for that exception or interrupt condition, saves state, and switches control.
[src:modula-3/exception-handling] Exception handling in the IEEE 754 floating-point standard refers in general to exceptional conditions and defines an exception as "an event that occurs when an operation on some particular operands has no outcome suitable for every reasonable application.
[src:modula-3/exception-handling] An exception-handling style enabled by the use of status flags involves: first computing an expression using a fast, direct implementation; checking whether it failed by testing status flags; and then, if necessary, calling a slower, more numerically robust, implementation.
[src:modula-3/exception-handling] The IEEE 754 standard uses the term "trapping" to refer to the calling of a user-supplied exception-handling routine on exceptional conditions, and is an optional feature of the standard.
[src:modula-3/exception-handling] The standard recommends several usage scenarios for this, including the implementation of non-default pre-substitution of a value followed by resumption, to concisely handle removable singularities.
[src:modula-3/exception-handling] The default IEEE 754 exception handling behaviour of resumption following pre-substitution of a default value avoids the risks inherent in changing flow of program control on numerical exceptions.
[src:modula-3/exception-handling] For example, the 1996 Cluster spacecraft launch ended in a catastrophic explosion due in part to the Ada exception handling policy of aborting computation on arithmetic error.
[src:modula-3/exception-handling] William Kahan claims the default IEEE 754 exception handling behavior would have prevented this.
[src:modula-3/exception-handling] In computer programming, several programming language mechanisms exist for exception handling.
[src:modula-3/exception-handling] The term *exception* is typically used to denote a data structure storing information about an exceptional condition.
[src:modula-3/exception-handling] One mechanism to transfer control, or *raise* an exception, is known as a *throw*; the exception is said to be *thrown*.
[src:modula-3/exception-handling] Front-end web development frameworks, such as React and Vue, have introduced error handling mechanisms where errors propagate up the user interface (UI) component hierarchy, in a way that is analogous to how errors propagate up the call stack in executing code.
[src:modula-3/exception-handling] Here the error boundary mechanism serves as an analogue to the typical try-catch mechanism.
[src:modula-3/exception-handling] Thus a component can ensure that errors from its child components are caught and handled, and not propagated up to parent components.
[src:modula-3/exception-handling] The error produced by the child component is caught and handled by the parent component.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] In computer science, **garbage collection** (**GC**) is a form of automatic memory management.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] The *garbage collector* attempts to reclaim memory that was allocated by the program, but is no longer referenced; such memory is called *garbage*.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] Garbage collection was invented by American computer scientist John McCarthy around 1959 to simplify manual memory management in Lisp.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] Garbage collection relieves the programmer from doing manual memory management, where the programmer specifies what objects to de-allocate and return to the memory system and when to do so.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] Other, similar techniques include stack allocation, region inference, and memory ownership, and combinations thereof.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] Garbage collection may take a significant proportion of a program's total processing time, and affect performance as a result.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] Resources other than memory, such as network sockets, database handles, windows, file descriptors, and device descriptors, are not typically handled by garbage collection, but rather by other methods (e.g. destructors).
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] Some such methods de-allocate memory also.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] Many programming languages require garbage collection, either as part of the language specification (e.g., RPL, Java, C#, D, Go, and most scripting languages) or effectively for practical implementation (e.g., formal languages like lambda calculus).
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] These are said to be *garbage-collected languages*.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] Other languages, such as C and C++, were designed for use with manual memory management, but have garbage-collected implementations available.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] Some languages, like Ada, Modula-3, and C++/CLI, allow both garbage collection and manual memory management to co-exist in the same application by using separate heaps for collected and manually managed objects.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] Still others, like D, are garbage-collected but allow the user to manually delete objects or even disable garbage collection entirely when speed is required.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] Although many languages integrate GC into their compiler and runtime system, *post-hoc* GC systems also exist, such as Automatic Reference Counting (ARC).
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] Some of these *post-hoc* GC systems do not require recompilation.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] GC frees the programmer from manually de-allocating memory.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] GC uses computing resources to decide which memory to free.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] Therefore, the penalty for the convenience of not annotating object lifetime manually in the source code is overhead, which can impair program performance.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] A peer-reviewed paper from 2005 concluded that GC needs five times the memory to compensate for this overhead and to perform as fast as the same program using idealized explicit memory management.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] The comparison however is made to a program generated by inserting deallocation calls using an oracle, implemented by collecting traces from programs run under a profiler, and the program is only correct for one particular execution of the program.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] Interaction with memory hierarchy effects can make this overhead intolerable in circumstances that are hard to predict or to detect in routine testing.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] The impact on performance was given by Apple as a reason for not adopting garbage collection in iOS, despite it being the most desired feature.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] The moment when the garbage is actually collected can be unpredictable, resulting in stalls (pauses to shift/free memory) scattered throughout a session.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] Unpredictable stalls can be unacceptable in real-time environments, in transaction processing, or in interactive programs.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] Incremental, concurrent, and real-time garbage collectors address these problems, with varying trade-offs.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] Tracing garbage collection is the most common type of garbage collection, so much so that "garbage collection" often refers to tracing garbage collection, rather than other methods such as reference counting.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] The overall strategy consists of determining which objects should be garbage collected by tracing which objects are *reachable* by a chain of references from certain root objects, and considering the rest as garbage and collecting them.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] However, there are a large number of algorithms used in implementation, with widely varying complexity and performance characteristics.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] Reference counting garbage collection is where each object has a count of the number of references to it.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] Garbage is identified by having a reference count of zero.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] An object's reference count is incremented when a reference to it is created and decremented when a reference is destroyed.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] When the count reaches zero, the object's memory is reclaimed.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] If two or more objects refer to each other, they can create a cycle whereby neither will be collected as their mutual references never let their reference counts become zero.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] ) use specific cycle-detecting algorithms to deal with this issue.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] for the "backpointers" which create cycles.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] Under reference counting, a weak reference is similar to a weak reference under a tracing garbage collector.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] It is a special reference object whose existence does not increment the reference count of the referent object.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] , rather than being permitted to remain dangling, meaning that it turns into a predictable value, such as a null reference.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] Reference counting requires space to be allocated for each object to store its reference count.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] The count may be stored adjacent to the object's memory or in a side table somewhere else, but in either case, every single reference-counted object requires additional storage for its reference count.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] Memory space with the size of an unsigned pointer is commonly used for this task, meaning that 32 or 64 bits of reference count storage must be allocated for each object.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] to store the reference count in unused areas of the object's memory.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] Often, an architecture does not actually allow programs to access the full range of memory addresses that could be stored in its native pointer size; a certain number of high bits in the address is either ignored or required to be zero.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] If an object reliably has a pointer at a certain location, the reference count can be stored in the unused bits of the pointer.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] , 19 unused bits of this class pointer are used to store the object's reference count.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] In naive implementations, each assignment of a reference and each reference falling out of scope often require modifications of one or more reference counters.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] However, in a common case when a reference is copied from an outer scope variable into an inner scope variable, such that the lifetime of the inner variable is bounded by the lifetime of the outer one, the reference incrementing can be eliminated.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] The outer variable "owns" the reference.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] whose constructors, destructors, and assignment operators manage the references.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] A smart pointer can be passed by reference to a function, which avoids the need to copy-construct a new smart pointer (which would increase the reference count on entry into the function and decrease it on exit).
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] Instead, the function receives a reference to the smart pointer which is produced inexpensively.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] The Deutsch-Bobrow method of reference counting capitalizes on the fact that most reference count updates are in fact generated by references stored in local variables.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] It ignores these references, only counting references in the heap, but before an object with reference count zero can be deleted, the system must verify with a scan of the stack and register that no other reference to it still exists.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] Consider a pointer that in a given interval of the execution is updated several times.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] But most of these updates are redundant.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] Levanoni and Petrank measured an elimination of more than 99% of the counter updates in typical Java benchmarks.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] , at least for any objects which are shared, or potentially shared among multiple threads.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] Atomic operations are expensive on a multiprocessor, and even more expensive if they have to be emulated with software algorithms.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] can be used to eliminate all atomic operations from the write-barrier.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] Counters are never updated by the program threads in the course of program execution.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] They are only modified by the collector which executes as a single additional thread with no synchronization.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] This method can be used as a stop-the-world mechanism for parallel programs, and also with a concurrent reference counting collector.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] Naive implementations of reference counting do not generally provide real-time behavior, because any pointer assignment can potentially cause a number of objects bounded only by total allocated memory size to be recursively freed while the thread is unable to perform other work.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] It is possible to avoid this issue by delegating the freeing of unreferenced objects to other threads, at the cost of extra overhead.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] Escape analysis is a compile-time technique that can convert heap allocations to stack allocations, thereby reducing the amount of garbage collection to be done.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] This analysis determines whether an object allocated inside a function is accessible outside of it.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] If a function-local allocation is found to be accessible to another function or thread, the allocation is said to "escape" and cannot be done on the stack.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] Otherwise, the object may be allocated directly on the stack and released when the function returns, bypassing the heap and associated memory management costs.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] Generally speaking, higher-level programming languages are more likely to have garbage collection as a standard feature.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] In some languages lacking built-in garbage collection, it can be added through a library, as with the Boehm garbage collector for C and C++.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] Most functional programming languages, such as ML, Haskell, and APL, have garbage collection built in.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] Lisp is especially notable as both the first functional programming language and the first language to introduce garbage collection.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] Other dynamic languages, such as Ruby and Julia (but not Perl 5 or PHP before version 5.3, which both use reference counting), JavaScript and ECMAScript also tend to use GC.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] Object-oriented programming languages such as Smalltalk, ooRexx, RPL and Java usually provide integrated garbage collection.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] Notable exceptions are C++ and Delphi, which have destructors.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] BASIC and Logo have often used garbage collection for variable-length data types, such as strings and lists, so as not to burden programmers with memory management details.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] On the Altair 8800, programs with many string variables and little string space could cause long pauses due to garbage collection.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] Similarly the Applesoft BASIC interpreter's garbage collection algorithm repeatedly scans the string descriptors for the string having the highest address in order to compact it toward high memory, resulting in $O(n^{2})$ performance and pauses anywhere from a few seconds to a few minutes.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] A replacement garbage collector for Applesoft BASIC by Randy Wigginton identifies a group of strings in every pass over the heap, reducing collection time dramatically.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] BASIC.SYSTEM, released with ProDOS in 1983, provides a windowing garbage collector for BASIC that is many times faster.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] C has never offered official support for garbage collection.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] C++ added garbage collection support in C++11 to the standard library, however this was removed in C++23 due to no compilers implementing support for the feature.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] The features that were part of this were related to pointer safety.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] Although garbage collection support in the standard library was removed, some garbage collectors such as Boehm garbage collector (for C and C++) can still be used.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] Boehm GC uses mark-and-sweep garbage collection.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] It can also be used in leak detection mode, where memory management is still manual however leaks and double-free errors can be detected and reported.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] Its use can be called from the header `<gc.h>`.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] One can still abstract away manual object destructions in C++ by using the "resource acquisition is initialization" (RAII) idiom and smart pointers.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] `std::unique_ptr` ties lifetimes to ownership, while `std::shared_ptr` uses reference counting to determine lifetime.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] `std::weak_ptr` can be used to obtain a pointer without increasing the reference count.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] Unlike garbage collection, RAII is deterministic.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] While the Objective-C traditionally had no garbage collection, with the release of OS X 10.5 in 2007 Apple introduced garbage collection for Objective-C 2.0, using an in-house developed runtime collector.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] However, with the 2012 release of OS X 10.8, garbage collection was deprecated in favor of LLVM's automatic reference counter (ARC) that was introduced with OS X 10.7.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] Furthermore, since May 2015 Apple even forbade the usage of garbage collection for new OS X applications in the App Store.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] For iOS, garbage collection has never been introduced due to problems in application responsivity and performance; instead, iOS uses ARC.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] Garbage collection is rarely used on embedded or real-time systems because of the usual need for very tight control over the use of limited resources.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] However, garbage collectors compatible with many limited environments have been developed.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] The Microsoft .NET Micro Framework, .NET nanoFramework and Java Platform, Micro Edition are embedded software platforms that, like their larger cousins, include garbage collection.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] Compile-time garbage collection is a form of static analysis allowing memory to be reused and reclaimed based on invariants known during compilation.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] This form of garbage collection has been studied in the Mercury programming language, and it saw greater usage with the introduction of LLVM's automatic reference counter (ARC) into Apple's ecosystem (iOS and OS X) in 2011.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] Incremental, concurrent, and real-time garbage collectors have been developed, for example by Henry Baker and by Henry Lieberman.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] In Baker's algorithm, the allocation is done in either half of a single region of memory.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] When it becomes half full, a garbage collection is performed which moves the live objects into the other half and the remaining objects are implicitly deallocated.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] The running program (the 'mutator') has to check that any object it references is in the correct half, and if not move it across, while a background task is finding all of the objects.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] Generational garbage collection schemes are based on the empirical observation that most objects die young.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] In generational garbage collection, two or more allocation regions (generations) are kept, which are kept separate based on the object's age.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] New objects are created in the "young" generation that is regularly collected, and when a generation is full, the objects that are still referenced from older regions are copied into the next oldest generation.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] Some high-level language computer architectures include hardware support for real-time garbage collection.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] Most implementations of real-time garbage collectors use tracing.
[src:modula-3/garbage-collection-computer-science] Such real-time garbage collectors meet hard real-time constraints when used with a real-time operating system.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Generic programming was introduced to the mainstream with Ada in 1977.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] With templates in C++, generic programming became part of the repertoire of professional library design.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] The techniques were further improved and *parameterized types* were introduced in the influential 1994 book *Design Patterns*.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] New techniques were introduced by Andrei Alexandrescu in his 2001 book *Modern C++ Design: Generic Programming and Design Patterns Applied*.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Subsequently, D implemented the same ideas.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Such software entities are known as *generics* in Ada, C#, Delphi, Eiffel, F#, Java, Mojo, Nim, Python, Go, Rust, Swift, TypeScript, and Visual Basic (.NET).
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] They are known as *parametric polymorphism* in ML, Scala, Julia, and Haskell.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] The "generic programming" paradigm is an approach to software decomposition whereby fundamental requirements on types are abstracted from across concrete examples of algorithms and data structures and formalized as concepts, analogously to the abstraction of algebraic theories in abstract algebra.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Early examples of this programming approach were implemented in Scheme and Ada, although the best known example is the Standard Template Library (STL), which developed a theory of iterators that is used to decouple sequence data structures and the algorithms operating on them.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] For example, given *N* sequence data structures, e.g. singly linked list, vector etc., and *M* algorithms to operate on them, e.g.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] `find`, `sort` etc., a direct approach would implement each algorithm specifically for each data structure, giving *N* × *M* combinations to implement.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Thus, only *N* + *M* data structure-algorithm combinations need be implemented.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] An important point is that a data structure will return a model of the most general concept that can be implemented efficiently—computational complexity requirements are explicitly part of the concept definition.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] This limits the data structures a given algorithm can be applied to and such complexity requirements are a major determinant of data structure choice.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Generic programming similarly has been applied in other domains, e.g. graph algorithms.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Although this approach often uses language features of compile-time genericity and templates, it is independent of particular language-technical details.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] — Alexander Stepanov, An Interview with A.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Other programming paradigms that have been described as generic programming include *Datatype generic programming* as described in "Generic Programming – an Introduction".
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] The *Scrap your boilerplate* approach is a lightweight generic programming approach for Haskell.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] In this article we distinguish the high-level programming paradigms of *generic programming*, above, from the lower-level programming language *genericity mechanisms* used to implement them (see Programming language support for genericity).
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] For further discussion and comparison of generic programming paradigms, see.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Genericity facilities have existed in high-level languages since at least the 1970s in languages such as ML, CLU and Ada, and were subsequently adopted by many object-based and object-oriented languages, including BETA, C++, D, Eiffel, Java, and DEC's now defunct Trellis-Owl.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Genericity is implemented and supported differently in various programming languages; the term "generic" has also been used differently in various programming contexts.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] For example, in Forth the compiler can execute code while compiling and one can create new *compiler keywords* and new implementations for those words on the fly.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] It has few *words* that expose the compiler behaviour and therefore naturally offers *genericity* capacities that, however, are not referred to as such in most Forth texts.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] The term has been used in functional programming, specifically in Haskell-like languages, which use a structural type system where types are always parametric and the actual code on those types is generic.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] These uses still serve a similar purpose of code-saving and rendering an abstraction.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Arrays and structs can be viewed as predefined generic types.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Every usage of an array or struct type instantiates a new concrete type, or reuses a previous instantiated type.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Array element types and struct element types are parameterized types, which are used to instantiate the corresponding generic type.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] All this is usually built-in in the compiler and the syntax differs from other generic constructs.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Some extensible programming languages try to unify built-in and user defined generic types.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] A broad survey of genericity mechanisms in programming languages follows.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] For a specific survey comparing suitability of mechanisms for generic programming, see.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] When creating container classes in statically typed languages, it is inconvenient to write specific implementations for each datatype contained, especially if the code for each datatype is virtually identical.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Above, `T` is a placeholder for whatever type is specified when the list is created.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] These "generic objects of type `T`", commonly called templates, allow a class to be reused with different datatypes as long as certain contracts such as subtypes and signature are kept.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] This genericity mechanism should not be confused with *inclusion polymorphism*, which is the algorithmic usage of exchangeable sub-classes: for instance, a list of objects of type `MovingEntity` containing objects of type `Animal` and `Car`.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] The C++ `template` construct used above is widely cited as the genericity construct that popularized the notion among programmers and language designers and supports many generic programming idioms.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] The D language also offers fully generic-capable templates based on the C++ precedent but with a simplified syntax.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] The Java language has provided genericity facilities syntactically based on C++'s since the introduction of Java Platform, Standard Edition (J2SE) 5.0.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] C# 2.0, Oxygene 1.5 (formerly Chrome) and Visual Basic (.NET) 2005 have constructs that exploit the support for generics present in Microsoft .NET Framework since version 2.0.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Ada has had generics since it was first designed in 1977–1980.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] The standard library uses generics to provide many services.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Ada 2005 adds a comprehensive generic container library to the standard library, which was inspired by C++'s Standard Template Library.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] A *generic unit* is a package or a subprogram that takes one or more *generic formal parameters*.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] A *generic formal parameter* is a value, a variable, a constant, a type, a subprogram, or even an instance of another, designated, generic unit.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] For generic formal types, the syntax distinguishes between discrete, floating-point, fixed-point, access (pointer) types, etc.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Some formal parameters can have default values.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] To *instantiate* a generic unit, the programmer passes *actual* parameters for each formal.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] The generic instance then behaves just like any other unit.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] It is possible to instantiate generic units at run-time, for example, inside a loop.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] The language syntax allows precise specification of constraints on generic formal parameters.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] For example, it is possible to specify that a generic formal type will only accept a modular type as the actual.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] In this example, `Array_Type` is constrained by both `Index_Type` and `Element_Type`.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] When instantiating the unit, the programmer must pass an actual array type that satisfies these constraints.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] The disadvantage of this fine-grained control is a complicated syntax, but, because all generic formal parameters are completely defined in the specification, the compiler can instantiate generics without looking at the body of the generic.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Unlike C++, Ada does not allow specialised generic instances, and requires that all generics be instantiated explicitly.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] C++ uses templates to enable generic programming techniques.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] The C++ Standard Library includes the Standard Template Library or STL that provides a framework of templates for common data structures and algorithms.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Templates in C++ may also be used for template metaprogramming, which is a way of pre-evaluating some of the code at compile-time rather than run-time.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Using template specialization, C++ Templates are Turing complete.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] There are many kinds of templates, the most common being function templates and class templates.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] A *function template* is a pattern for creating ordinary functions based upon the parameterizing types supplied when instantiated.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] For example, the C++ Standard Template Library contains the function template `std::max(x, y)` that creates functions that return either `x` or `y`, whichever is larger.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] The compiler examines the arguments used to call `max` and determines that this is a call to `max(int, int)`.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] This works whether the arguments `x` and `y` are integers, strings, or any other type for which the expression `x < y` is sensible, or more specifically, for any type for which `operator<` is defined.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Common inheritance is not needed for the set of types that can be used, and so it is very similar to duck typing.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] A program defining a custom data type can use operator overloading to define the meaning of `<` for that type, thus allowing its use with the `std::max()` function template.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] While this may seem a minor benefit in this isolated example, in the context of a comprehensive library like the STL it allows the programmer to get extensive functionality for a new data type, just by defining a few operators for it.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Merely defining `<` allows a type to be used with the standard `std::sort()`, `std::stable_sort()`, and `std::binary_search()` algorithms or to be put inside data structures such as `std::set<T>`s (equivalent to `TreeSet<T>`, heaps, and associative arrays.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] C++ templates are completely type safe at compile time.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] As a demonstration, the standard type `std::complex<T>` does not define the `<` operator, because there is no strict order on complex numbers.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Therefore, `std::max(x, y)` will fail with a compile error, if `x` and `y` are `complex` values.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Likewise, other templates that rely on `<` cannot be applied to `complex` data unless a comparison (in the form of a functor or function) is provided.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] For instance, `std::complex<T>` cannot be used as key for a `std::map<K, V>` (equivalent to `TreeMap<K, V>`) unless a comparison is provided.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Unfortunately, compilers historically generate somewhat esoteric, long, and unhelpful error messages for this sort of error.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Ensuring that a certain object adheres to a method protocol can alleviate this issue.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Languages which use `std::compare` instead of `<` can also use `std::complex<T>` values as keys.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Another kind of template, a *class template*, extends the same concept to classes.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] A class template specialization is a class.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Class templates are often used to make generic containers.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] For example, the STL has a doubly linked list container, `std::list<T>` (equivalent to `LinkedList<T>`).
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] To make a linked list of integers, one writes `list<int>`, while a list of strings is denoted `list<string>`.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] A `std::list<T>` has a set of standard functions associated with it, that work for any compatible parameterizing types.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] C++20 introduces constraining template types using concepts.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] A powerful feature of C++'s templates is *template specialization*.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] This allows alternative implementations to be provided based on certain characteristics of the parameterized type that is being instantiated.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Template specialization has two purposes: to allow certain forms of optimization, and to reduce code bloat.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] For example, consider a `sort()` template function.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] One of the primary activities that such a function does is to swap or exchange the values in two of the container's positions.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] If the values are large (in terms of the number of bytes it takes to store each of them), then it is often quicker to first build a separate list of pointers to the objects, sort those pointers, and then build the final sorted sequence.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] If the values are quite small however it is usually fastest to just swap the values in-place as needed.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Furthermore, if the parameterized type is already of some pointer-type, then there is no need to build a separate pointer array.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Template specialization allows the template creator to write different implementations and to specify the characteristics that the parameterized type(s) must have for each implementation to be used.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Unlike function templates, class templates can be partially specialized.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] That means that an alternate version of the class template code can be provided when some of the template parameters are known, while leaving other template parameters generic.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] This can be used, for example, to create a default implementation (the *primary specialization*) that assumes that copying a parameterizing type is expensive and then create partial specializations for types that are cheap to copy, thus increasing overall efficiency.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Clients of such a class template just use specializations of it without needing to know whether the compiler used the primary specialization or some partial specialization in each case.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Class templates can also be *fully specialized,* which means that an alternate implementation can be provided when all of the parameterizing types are known.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Some uses of templates, such as the `max()` function, were formerly filled by function-like preprocessor macros (a legacy of the C language).
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Macros are expanded (copy pasted) by the preprocessor, before program compiling; templates are actual real functions.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Macros are always expanded inline; templates can also be inline functions when the compiler deems it appropriate.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] However, templates are generally considered an improvement over macros for these purposes.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Templates avoid some of the common errors found in code that makes heavy use of function-like macros, such as evaluating parameters with side effects twice.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Perhaps most importantly, templates were designed to be applicable to much larger problems than macros.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Many compilers historically had poor support for templates, thus the use of templates could make code somewhat less portable.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Support may also be poor when a C++ compiler is being used with a linker that is not C++-aware, or when attempting to use templates across shared library boundaries.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Compilers can produce confusing, long, and sometimes unhelpful error messages when errors are detected in code that uses SFINAE.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] This can make templates difficult to develop with.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Finally, the use of templates requires the compiler to generate a separate *instance* of the templated class or function for every type parameters used with it.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] (This is necessary because types in C++ are not all the same size, and the sizes of data fields are important to how classes work.) So the indiscriminate use of templates can lead to code bloat, resulting in excessively large executables.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] However, judicious use of template specialization and derivation can dramatically reduce such code bloat in some cases:So, can derivation be used to reduce the problem of code replicated because templates are used?
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] This would involve deriving a template from an ordinary class.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] This technique proved successful in curbing code bloat in real use.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Templated classes or functions may require an *explicit specialization* of the template class which would require rewriting of an entire class for a specific template parameters used by it.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] The extra instantiations generated by templates can also cause some debuggers to have difficulty working gracefully with templates.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] For example, setting a debug breakpoint within a template from a source file may either miss setting the breakpoint in the actual instantiation desired or may set a breakpoint in every place the template is instantiated.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Also, the implementation source code for the template must be completely available (e.g. included in a header) to the translation unit (source file) using it.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Templates, including much of the Standard Library, if not included in header files, cannot be compiled.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] (This is in contrast to non-templated code, which may be compiled to binary, providing only a declarations header file for code using it.) This may be a disadvantage by exposing the implementing code, which removes some abstractions, and could restrict its use in closed-source projects.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] The D language supports templates based in design on C++.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Templates in D use a different syntax than in C++: whereas in C++ template parameters are wrapped in angular brackets (`Template<param1, param2>`), D uses an exclamation sign and parentheses: `Template!(param1, param2)`.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] This avoids the C++ parsing difficulties due to ambiguity with comparison operators.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] If there is only one parameter, the parentheses can be omitted.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Conventionally, D combines the above features to provide compile-time polymorphism using trait-based generic programming.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Combining the above allows generating code based on existing declarations.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] For example, D serialization frameworks can enumerate a type's members and generate specialized functions for each serialized type to perform serialization and deserialization.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] User-defined attributes could further indicate serialization rules.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] The `import` expression and compile-time function execution also allow efficiently implementing domain-specific languages.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Generic classes have been a part of Eiffel since the original method and language design.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] The foundation publications of Eiffel, use the term *genericity* to describe creating and using generic classes.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Generic classes are declared with their class name and a list of one or more *formal generic parameters*.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] The formal generic parameters are placeholders for arbitrary class names that will be supplied when a declaration of the generic class is made, as shown in the two *generic derivations* below, where `ACCOUNT` and `DEPOSIT` are other class names.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] `ACCOUNT` and `DEPOSIT` are considered *actual generic parameters* as they provide real class names to substitute for `G` in actual use.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Within the Eiffel type system, although class `LIST [G]` is considered a class, it is not considered a type.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] However, a generic derivation of `LIST [G]` such as `LIST [ACCOUNT]` is considered a type.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] For the list class shown above, an actual generic parameter substituting for `G` can be any other available class.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] To constrain the set of classes from which valid actual generic parameters can be chosen, a *generic constraint* can be specified.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] In the declaration of class `SORTED_LIST` below, the generic constraint dictates that any valid actual generic parameter will be a class that inherits from class `COMPARABLE`.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] The generic constraint ensures that elements of a `SORTED_LIST` can in fact be sorted.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Support for the *generics*, or "containers-of-type-T" was added to the Java programming language in 2004 as part of J2SE 5.0.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] In Java, generics are only checked at compile time for type correctness.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] The generic type information is then removed via a process called type erasure, to maintain compatibility with old JVM implementations, making it unavailable at runtime.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] For example, a `List<String>` is converted to the raw type `java.util.List`.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] The compiler inserts type casts to convert the elements to the `java.lang.String` type when they are retrieved from the list, reducing performance compared to other implementations such as C++ templates.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Generics were added as part of .NET Framework 2.0 in November 2005, based on a research prototype from Microsoft Research started in 1999.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Although similar to generics in Java, .NET generics do not apply type erasure, but implement generics as a first class mechanism in the runtime using reification.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] This design choice provides additional functionality, such as allowing reflection with preservation of generic types, and alleviating some of the limits of erasure (such as being unable to create generic arrays).
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] This also means that there is no performance hit from runtime casts and normally expensive boxing conversions.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] When primitive and value types are used as generic arguments, they get specialized implementations, allowing for efficient generic collections and methods.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] As in C++ and Java, nested generic types such as `Dictionary<string, List<int>>` are valid types, however are advised against for member signatures in code analysis design rules.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] .NET allows six varieties of generic type constraints using the `where` keyword including restricting generic types to be value types, to be classes, to have constructors, and to implement interfaces.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] The `MakeAtLeast()` method allows operation on arrays, with elements of generic type `T`.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] The method's type constraint indicates that the method is applicable to any type `T` that implements the generic `System.IComparable<T>` interface.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] This ensures a compile time error, if the method is called if the type does not support comparison.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] The interface provides the generic method `CompareTo(T)`.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] The above method could also be written without generic types, simply using the non-generic `System.Array` type.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] However, since arrays are contravariant, the casting would not be type safe, and the compiler would be unable to find certain possible errors that would otherwise be caught when using generic types.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] In addition, the method would need to access the array items as `object`s instead, and would require casting to compare two elements.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] A notable behavior of static members in a generic .NET class is static member instantiation per run-time type (see example below).
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] For Pascal, generics were first implemented in 2006, in the implementation Free Pascal.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] The Object Pascal dialect Delphi acquired generics in the 2007 Delphi 11 release by CodeGear, initially only with the .NET compiler (since discontinued) before being added to the native code in the 2009 Delphi 12 release.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] The semantics and abilities of Delphi generics are largely modelled on those of generics in .NET 2.0, though the implementation is by necessity quite different.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] As with C#, methods and whole types can have one or more type parameters.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] In the example, TArray is a generic type (defined by the language) and MakeAtLeast a generic method.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] The available constraints are very similar to the available constraints in C#: any value type, any class, a specific class or interface, and a class with a parameterless constructor.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Multiple constraints act as an additive union.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Free Pascal implemented generics in 2006 in version 2.2.0, before Delphi and with different syntax and semantics.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] However, since FPC version 2.6.0, the Delphi-style syntax is available when using the language mode `{$mode Delphi}`.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Thus, Free Pascal code supports generics in either style.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] The type class mechanism of Haskell supports generic programming.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] All the necessary methods will be "derived" – that is, constructed automatically – based on the structure of the type.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] This results in an equality function (`==`) and a string representation function (`show`) being automatically defined for any type of the form `BinTree T` provided that `T` itself supports those operations.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Ralf Hinze (2004) has shown that a similar effect can be achieved for user-defined type classes by certain programming techniques.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Other researchers have proposed approaches to this and other kinds of genericity in the context of Haskell and extensions to Haskell (discussed below).
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] PolyP was the first generic programming language extension to Haskell.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] In PolyP, generic functions are called *polytypic*.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] The language introduces a special construct in which such polytypic functions can be defined via structural induction over the structure of the pattern functor of a regular datatype.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Regular datatypes in PolyP are a subset of Haskell datatypes.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] A regular datatype t must be of kind ** → **, and if *a* is the formal type argument in the definition, then all recursive calls to *t* must have the form *t a*.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] These restrictions rule out higher-kinded datatypes and nested datatypes, where the recursive calls are of a different form.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Generic Haskell is another extension to Haskell, developed at Utrecht University in the Netherlands.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] The resulting type-indexed value can be specialized to any type.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Clean offers generic programming based PolyP and the Generic Haskell as supported by the GHC ≥ 6.0.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] It parametrizes by kind as those but offers overloading.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Languages in the ML family support generic programming through parametric polymorphism and generic modules called *functors.* Both Standard ML and OCaml provide functors, which are similar to class templates and to Ada's generic packages.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Scheme syntactic abstractions also have a connection to genericity – these are in fact a superset of C++ templates.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] A Verilog module may take one or more parameters, to which their actual values are assigned upon the instantiation of the module.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] One example is a generic register array where the array width is given via a parameter.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Such an array, combined with a generic wire vector, can make a generic buffer or memory module with an arbitrary bit width out of a single module implementation.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] VHDL, being derived from Ada, also has generic abilities.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] C has a feature called "type-generic expressions" using the `_Generic` keyword: This feature gives C function overloading capabilities, but is not related to generic programming.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Generic programming can be achieved by using the preprocessor to define the generic code, with macro expansion taking the role of *instantiation*.
[src:modula-3/generic-programming] Sometimes, the non-standard extension "statement expressions" is used to simulate function-like behaviour for generic code.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] Modula-3's main features are modularity, simplicity and safety while preserving the power of a systems-programming language.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] Modula-3 aimed to continue the Pascal tradition of type safety, while introducing new constructs for practical real-world programming.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] In particular Modula-3 added support for generic programming (similar to templates), multithreading, exception handling, garbage collection, object-oriented programming, partial revelation, and explicit marking of unsafe code.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] The design goal of Modula-3 was a language that implements the most important features of modern imperative programming languages in quite basic forms.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] Thus allegedly dangerous and complicating features such as multiple inheritance and operator overloading were omitted.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] The Modula-3 project started in November 1986 when Maurice Wilkes wrote to Niklaus Wirth with some ideas for a new version of Modula.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] Wilkes had been working at DEC just prior to this point, and had returned to England and joined Olivetti's Research Strategy Board.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] Wirth had already moved on to Oberon, but had no problems with Wilkes's team continuing development under the Modula name.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] The language definition was completed in August 1988, and an updated version in January 1989.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] Compilers from DEC and Olivetti soon followed, and 3rd party implementations after that.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] As the revised Modula-3 Report states, the language was influenced by other languages such as Mesa, Cedar, Object Pascal, Oberon and Euclid.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] During the 1990s, Modula-3 gained considerable currency as a teaching language, but it was never widely adopted for industrial use.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] Contributing to this may have been the demise of DEC, a key Modula-3 supporter (especially when it ceased to maintain it effectively before DEC was sold to Compaq in 1998).
[src:modula-3/modula-3] In any case, in spite of Modula-3's simplicity and power, it appears that there was little demand for a procedural compiled language with restricted implementation of object-oriented programming.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] Modula-3 is now taught in universities mostly in comparative programming language courses, and its textbooks are out of print.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] Essentially the only corporate supporter of Modula-3 is elego, which inherited the sources from Critical Mass and has since made several releases of the CM3 system in source and binary code.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] The Reactor IDE has been open source released after several years it had not, with the new name CM3-IDE.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] In March 2002, elego also took over the repository of another active Modula-3 distribution, PM3, until then maintained at the École Polytechnique de Montréal but which later continued by the work on HM3 improved over the years later until it was obsoleted.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] A common example of a language's syntax is the "Hello, World!" program.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] All programs in Modula-3 have at least a module file, while most also include an interface file that is used by clients to access data from the module.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] As in some other languages, a Modula-3 program must export a Main module, which can either be a file named Main.m3, or a file can call `EXPORT` to export the Main module.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] Module file names are advised to be the same as the name in source code.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] If they differ, the compiler only emits a warning.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] Other conventions in the syntax include naming the exported type of an interface `T`, since types are usually qualified by their full names, so a type `T` inside a module named Foo will be named `Foo.T`.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] Another similar convention is naming a public object `Public` as in the OOP examples below.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] First and foremost, all compiled units are either `INTERFACE` or implementation `MODULE`s, of one flavor or another.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] An interface compiled unit, starting with the keyword `INTERFACE`, defines constants, types, variables, exceptions, and procedures.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] The implementation module, starting with the keyword `MODULE`, provides the code, and any further constants, types, or variables needed to implement the interface.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] By default, an implementation module will implement the interface of the same name, but a module may explicitly `EXPORT` to a module not of the same name.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] For example, the main program exports an implementation module for the Main interface.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] Any compiled unit may `IMPORT` other interfaces, although circular imports are forbidden.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] This may be resolved by doing the import from the implementation MODULE.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] Typically, one only imports the interface, and uses the 'dot' notation to access the items within the interface (similar to accessing the fields within a record).
[src:modula-3/modula-3] A typical use is to define one data structure (record or object) per interface along with any support procedures.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] Here the main type will get the name 'T', and one uses as in `MyModule.T`.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] Some ability is deemed unsafe, where the compiler can no longer guarantee that results will be consistent; for example, when interfacing to the C language.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] The keyword `UNSAFE` prefixed in front of `INTERFACE` or `MODULE`, may be used to tell the compiler to enable certain low level features of the language.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] For example, an unsafe operation is bypassing the type system using `LOOPHOLE` to copy the bits of an integer into a floating point `REAL` number.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] An interface that imports an unsafe module must also be unsafe.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] A safe interface may be exported by an unsafe implementation module.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] This is the typical use when interfacing to external libraries, where two interfaces are built: one unsafe, the other safe.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] A generic interface and its corresponding generic module, prefix the `INTERFACE` or `MODULE` keyword with `GENERIC`, and take as formal arguments other interfaces.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] Thus (like C++ templates) one can easily define and use abstract data types, but unlike C++, the granularity is at the module level.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] An interface is passed to the generic interface and implementation modules as arguments, and the compiler will generate concrete modules.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] For example, one could define a GenericStack, then instantiate it with interfaces such as `IntegerElem`, or `RealElem`, or even interfaces to Objects, as long as each of those interfaces defines the properties needed by the generic modules.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] The bare types `INTEGER`, or `REAL` can't be used, because they are not modules, and the system of generics is based on using modules as arguments.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] By comparison, in a C++ template, a bare type would be used.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] Any identifier can be traced back to where it originated, unlike the 'include' feature of other languages.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] A compiled unit must import identifiers from other compiled units, using an `IMPORT` statement.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] Even enumerations make use of the same 'dot' notation as used when accessing a field of a record.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] Modula-3 supports the allocation of data at runtime.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] There are two kinds of memory that can be allocated, `TRACED` and `UNTRACED`, the difference being whether the garbage collector can see it or not.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] `NEW()` is used to allocate data of either of these classes of memory.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] In an `UNSAFE` module, `DISPOSE` is available to free untraced memory.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] Object-oriented programming techniques may be used in Modula-3, but their use is not a requirement.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] Many of the other features provided in Modula-3 (modules, generics) can usually take the place of object-orientation.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] Object support is intentionally kept to its simplest terms.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] An object type (termed a "class" in other object-oriented languages) is introduced with the `OBJECT` declaration, which has essentially the same syntax as a `RECORD` declaration, although an object type is a reference type, whereas RECORDs in Modula-3 are not (similar to structs in C).
[src:modula-3/modula-3] Exported types are usually named T by convention, and create a separate "Public" type to expose the methods and data.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] This defines an interface `Person` with two types, `T`, and `Public`, which is defined as an object with two methods, `getAge()` and `init()`.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] `T` is defined as a subtype of `Public` by the use of the `<:` operator.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] Modula-3's `REVEAL` construct provides a conceptually simple and clean yet very powerful mechanism for hiding implementation details from clients, with arbitrarily many levels of *friendliness*.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] A full revelation of the form `REVEAL T = V` can be used to show the full implementation of the `Person` interface from above.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] A partial revelation of the form `REVEAL T <: V` merely reveals that T is a supertype of V without revealing any additional information on T.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] Note the use of the `BRANDED` keyword, which "brands" objects to make them unique as to avoid structural equivalence.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] `BRANDED` can also take a string as an argument, but when omitted, a unique string is generated for you.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] Modula-3 is one of a few programming languages which requires external references from a module to be strictly qualified.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] That is, a reference in module `A` to the object `x` exported from module `B` must take the form `B.x`.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] In Modula-3, it is impossible to import *all exported names* from a module.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] Because of the language's requirements on name qualification and method overriding, it is impossible to break a working program simply by adding new declarations to an interface (any interface).
[src:modula-3/modula-3] This makes it possible for large programs to be edited concurrently by many programmers with no worries about naming conflicts; and it also makes it possible to edit core language libraries with the firm knowledge that no extant program will be *broken* in the process.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] Exception handling is based on a `TRY`...`EXCEPT` block system, which has since become common.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] One feature that has not been adopted in other languages, with the notable exceptions of Delphi, Python, Scala and Visual Basic.NET, is that the `EXCEPT` construct defined a form of switch statement with each possible exception as a case in its own EXCEPT clause.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] Modula-3 also supports a `LOOP`...`EXIT`...`END` construct that loops until an `EXIT` occurs, a structure equivalent to a simple loop inside a `TRY`...`EXCEPT` clause.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] The language supports the use of multi-threading, and synchronization between threads.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] There is a standard module within the runtime library (*m3core*) named Thread, which supports the use of multi-threaded applications.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] The Modula-3 runtime may make use of a separate thread for internal tasks such as garbage collection.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] A built-in data structure `MUTEX` is used to synchronize multiple threads and protect data structures from simultaneous access with possible corruption or race conditions.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] The `LOCK` statement introduces a block in which the mutex is locked.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] Unlocking a `MUTEX` is implicit by the code execution locus's leaving the block.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] The `MUTEX` is an object, and as such, other objects may be derived from it.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] For example, in the input/output (I/O) section of the library *libm3*, readers and writers (Rd.T, and Wr.T) are derived from MUTEX, and they lock themselves before accessing or modifying any internal data such as buffers.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] In *Systems Programming with Modula-3*, four essential points of the language design are intensively discussed.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] These topics are: structural vs. name equivalence, subtyping rules, generic modules, and parameter modes like `READONLY`.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] Continuing a trend started with the C language, many of the features needed to write real programs were left out of the language definition and instead provided via a standard library set.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] Standard libraries providing the following features.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] These are called standard interfaces and are required (must be provided) in the language.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] As in C, I/O is also provided via libraries, in Modula-3 called `Rd` and `Wr`.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] The object-oriented design of the Rd (readers) and Wr (writers) libraries is covered in detail in the book by Greg Nelson.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] An interesting aspect of Modula-3 is that it is one of few programming languages which standard libraries have been formally verified not to contain various types of bugs, including locking bugs.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] This was done under the auspices of the Larch/Modula-3 (see Larch family) and Extended static checking projects at DEC Systems Research Center.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] Several compilers are available, most of them open source.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] Since the only aspect of C data structures that is missing from Modula-3 is the union type, all extant Modula-3 implementations are able to provide good binary code compatibility with C language type declarations of arrays and structs.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] None of these books are still in print, although used copies are obtainable and some are partly or fully digitized, and some chapters of one have prior or posterior versions obtainable as research reports from the web.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] Although Modula-3 did not gain mainstream status, several parts of the DEC-SRC M3 distribution did.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] Probably the most influential part was the Network Objects library, which formed the basis for Java's first Remote Method Invocation (RMI) implementation, including the network protocol.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] Only when Sun moved from the Common Object Request Broker Architecture (CORBA) standard to the IIOP based protocol was it dropped.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] The Java documentation on garbage collection of remote objects still refer to the pioneering work done for Modula-3 Network Objects.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] Python's implementation of classes was also inspired by the class mechanism found in C++ and Modula-3.
[src:modula-3/modula-3] Also the language Nim makes use of some aspects of Modula-3, such as traced vs untraced pointers.
[src:modula-3/modular-programming] A module interface expresses the elements that are provided and required by the module.
[src:modula-3/modular-programming] The elements defined in the interface are detectable by other modules.
[src:modula-3/modular-programming] The implementation contains the working code that corresponds to the elements declared in the interface.
[src:modula-3/modular-programming] Modular programming, in the form of subsystems (particularly for I/O) and software libraries, dates to early software systems, where it was used for code reuse.
[src:modula-3/modular-programming] Modular programming per se, with a goal of modularity, developed in the late 1960s and 1970s, as a larger-scale analog of the concept of structured programming (1960s).
[src:modula-3/modular-programming] The term "modular programming" dates at least to the National Symposium on Modular Programming, organized at the Information and Systems Institute in July 1968 by Larry Constantine; other key concepts were information hiding (1972) and separation of concerns (SoC, 1974).
[src:modula-3/modular-programming] Modules were not included in the original specification for ALGOL 68 (1968), but were included as extensions in early implementations, ALGOL 68-R (1970) and ALGOL 68C (1970), and later formalized.
[src:modula-3/modular-programming] One of the first languages designed from the start for modular programming was the short-lived Modula (1975), by Niklaus Wirth.
[src:modula-3/modular-programming] Another early modular language was Mesa (1970s), by Xerox PARC, and Wirth drew on Mesa as well as the original Modula in its successor, Modula-2 (1978), which influenced later languages, particularly through its successor, Modula-3 (1980s).
[src:modula-3/modular-programming] Modula's use of dot-qualified names, like `M.a` to refer to object `a` from module `M`, coincides with notation to access a field of a record (and similarly for attributes or methods of objects), and is now widespread, seen in C++, C#, Dart, Go, Java, OCaml, and Python, among others.
[src:modula-3/modular-programming] Modular programming became widespread from the 1980s: the original Pascal language (1970) did not include modules, but later versions, notably UCSD Pascal (1978) and Turbo Pascal (1983) included them in the form of "units", as did the Pascal-influenced Ada (1980).
[src:modula-3/modular-programming] The Extended Pascal ISO 10206:1990 standard kept closer to Modula2 in its modular support.
[src:modula-3/modular-programming] Standard ML (1984) has one of the most complete module systems, including functors (parameterized modules) to map between modules.
[src:modula-3/modular-programming] In the 1980s and 1990s, modular programming was overshadowed by and often conflated with object-oriented programming, particularly due to the popularity of C++ and Java.
[src:modula-3/modular-programming] For example, the C family of languages had support for objects and classes in C++ (originally C with Classes, 1980) and Objective-C (1983), only supporting modules 30 years or more later.
[src:modula-3/modular-programming] Java (1995) supports modules in the form of packages, though the primary unit of code organization is a class.
[src:modula-3/modular-programming] However, Python (1991) prominently used both modules and objects from the start, using modules as the primary unit of code organization and "packages" as a larger-scale unit.
[src:modula-3/modular-programming] Perl 5 (1994) also includes support for both modules and objects, with a vast array of modules being available from CPAN (1993).
[src:modula-3/modular-programming] OCaml (1996) followed ML by supporting modules and functors.
[src:modula-3/modular-programming] Modular programming is now widespread, and found in virtually all major languages developed since the 1990s.
[src:modula-3/modular-programming] The relative importance of modules varies between languages, and in class-based object-oriented languages there is still overlap and confusion with classes as a unit of organization and encapsulation, but these are both well-established as distinct concepts.
[src:modula-3/modular-programming] The term *assembly* (as in .NET languages like C#, F#, or Visual Basic) or *package* (as in Dart, Go, or Java) is sometimes used instead of *module*.
[src:modula-3/modular-programming] In other implementations, these are distinct concepts; in Python a package is a set of modules, while in Java 9 the introduction of the Java Platform Module System, in which a new module concept, involving a set of packages with enhanced access control, was implemented.
[src:modula-3/modular-programming] In Java, the term *package* is used for the module concept in the Java language specification.
[src:modula-3/modular-programming] The *module*, a kind of set of a package, was introduced in Java 9.
[src:modula-3/modular-programming] In some Pascal dialects, the term *unit* is used for the module concept.
[src:modula-3/modular-programming] A component is a similar concept, but typically refers to a higher level; a component is a piece of a whole system, while a module is a piece of an individual program.
[src:modula-3/modular-programming] The scale of the term "module" varies significantly between languages; in Python it is very small-scale and each file is a module, while in Java 9 it is large-scale, where a module is a set of packages, which are in turn sets of files.
[src:modula-3/modular-programming] Conspicuous examples of languages that lack support for modules are C, and in their original forms, C++ and Pascal.
[src:modula-3/modular-programming] C and C++ do, however, allow separate compilation and declarative interfaces to be specified using header files which is commonly considered modularization.
[src:modula-3/modular-programming] Modules were added to Objective-C in iOS 7 (2013), and to C++ with C++20.
[src:modula-3/modular-programming] Pascal was superseded by Modula and Oberon, which included modules from the start, and various derivatives that included modules.
[src:modula-3/modular-programming] JavaScript has had native modules since ECMAScript 2015.
[src:modula-3/modular-programming] C++ modules have allowed backwards compatibility with headers (with "header units").
[src:modula-3/modular-programming] Dialects of C allow for modules, for example Clang supports modules for the C language, though the syntax and semantics of Clang C modules differ from C++ modules.
[src:modula-3/modular-programming] Modular programming can be performed even where the programming language lacks explicit syntactic features to support named modules, like, for example, in C.
[src:modula-3/modular-programming] This is done by using existing language features, together with, for example, coding conventions, programming idioms and the physical code structure.
[src:modula-3/modular-programming] IBM i also uses modules when programming in the Integrated Language Environment (ILE).
[src:modula-3/modular-programming] With modular programming, concerns are separated such that modules perform logically discrete functions, interacting through well-defined interfaces.
[src:modula-3/modular-programming] Often modules form a directed acyclic graph (DAG); in this case a cyclic dependency between modules is seen as indicating that these should be a single module.
[src:modula-3/modular-programming] In the case where modules do form a DAG they can be arranged as a hierarchy, where the lowest-level modules are independent, depending on no other modules, and higher-level modules depend on lower-level ones.
[src:modula-3/modular-programming] A particular program or library is a top-level module of its own hierarchy, but can in turn be seen as a lower-level module of a higher-level program, library, or system.
[src:modula-3/modular-programming] When creating a modular system, instead of creating a monolithic application (where the smallest component is the whole), several smaller modules are written separately so when they are composed together, they construct the executable application program.
[src:modula-3/modular-programming] Typically, these are also compiled separately, via separate compilation, and then linked by a linker.
[src:modula-3/modular-programming] A just-in-time compiler may perform some of this construction "on-the-fly" at run time.
[src:modula-3/modular-programming] These independent functions are commonly classified as either program control functions or specific task functions.
[src:modula-3/modular-programming] Program control functions are designed to work for one program.
[src:modula-3/modular-programming] Specific task functions are closely prepared to be applicable for various programs.
[src:modula-3/modular-programming] This makes modular designed systems, if built correctly, far more reusable than a traditional monolithic design, since all (or many) of these modules may then be reused (without change) in other projects.
[src:modula-3/modular-programming] This also facilitates the "breaking down" of projects into several smaller projects.
[src:modula-3/modular-programming] Theoretically, a modularized software project will be more easily assembled by large teams, since no team members are creating the whole system, or even need to know about the system as a whole.
[src:modula-3/modular-programming] They can focus just on the assigned smaller task.
[src:modula-3/type-system] A programming language consists of a system of allowed sequences of symbols (constructs) together with rules that define how each construct is interpreted.
[src:modula-3/type-system] For example, a language might allow expressions representing various types of data, expressions that provide structuring rules for data, expressions representing various operations on data, and constructs that provide sequencing rules for the order in which to perform operations.
[src:modula-3/type-system] A simple type system for a programming language is a set of rules that associates a *data type* (for example, integer, floating point, string) with each *term* (data-valued expression) in a computer program.
[src:modula-3/type-system] In more ambitious type systems, a variety of constructs, such as variables, expressions, functions, and modules, may be assigned types.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Type systems formalize and enforce the otherwise implicit categories the programmer uses for algebraic data types, data structures, or other data types, such as "string", "array of float", "function returning boolean".
[src:modula-3/type-system] The main purpose of a type system in a programming language is to reduce possibilities for bugs in computer programs due to mismatches in how values are interpreted in different parts of a program.
[src:modula-3/type-system] The aim is to prevent operations expecting a certain kind of value from being applied to values for which that operation does not make sense (validity errors).
[src:modula-3/type-system] A type system can detect and prevent some of these mismatches.
[src:modula-3/type-system] When a type mismatch is detected, it is called a type error.
[src:modula-3/type-system] The type of a term constrains the contexts in which it may be used.
[src:modula-3/type-system] For a variable, the type system determines the allowed values of that variable.
[src:modula-3/type-system] For that variable to be presented as a parameter to an operation, the operation must be able to accept in that parameter any value that the type of the variable allows.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Type systems are typically specified as part of programming language design.
[src:modula-3/type-system] They are built into interpreters and compilers for the language.
[src:modula-3/type-system] In some languages, the type system can be extended by optional tools that perform added checks using the language's original type syntax and grammar.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Type systems allow defining interfaces between different parts of a computer program, and then checking that the parts have been connected in a consistent way.
[src:modula-3/type-system] This checking can happen statically (at compile time), dynamically (at runtime), or as a combination of both.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Type systems have other purposes as well, such as expressing business rules, enabling certain compiler optimizations, allowing for multiple dispatch, and providing a form of documentation.
[src:modula-3/type-system] An example of a simple type system is that of the C language.
[src:modula-3/type-system] The portions of a C program are the function definitions.
[src:modula-3/type-system] One function is invoked by another function.
[src:modula-3/type-system] The interface of a function states the name of the function and a list of parameters that are passed to the function's code.
[src:modula-3/type-system] The code of an invoking function states the name of the invoked, along with the names of variables that hold values to pass to it.
[src:modula-3/type-system] During a computer program's execution, the values are placed into temporary storage, then execution jumps to the code of the invoked function.
[src:modula-3/type-system] The invoked function's code accesses the values and makes use of them.
[src:modula-3/type-system] If the instructions inside the function are written with the assumption of receiving an integer value, but the calling code passed a floating-point value, then the wrong result will be computed by the invoked function.
[src:modula-3/type-system] The C compiler checks the types of the arguments passed to a function when it is called against the types of the parameters declared in the function's definition.
[src:modula-3/type-system] If the types do not match, the compiler throws a compile-time error or warning.
[src:modula-3/type-system] A compiler may also use the static type of a value to optimize the storage it needs and the choice of algorithms for operations on the value.
[src:modula-3/type-system] In many C compilers the *float* data type, for example, is represented in 32 bits, in accord with the IEEE specification for single-precision floating point numbers.
[src:modula-3/type-system] They will thus use floating-point-specific microprocessor operations on those values (floating-point addition, multiplication, etc.).
[src:modula-3/type-system] The depth of type constraints and the manner of their evaluation affect the *typing* of the language.
[src:modula-3/type-system] A programming language may further associate an operation with various resolutions for each type, in the case of type polymorphism.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Type theory is the study of type systems.
[src:modula-3/type-system] The concrete types of some programming languages, such as integers and strings, depend on practical issues of computer architecture, compiler implementation, and language design.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Formally, type theory studies type systems.
[src:modula-3/type-system] A programming language must have the opportunity to type check using the *type system* whether at compile time or runtime, manually annotated or automatically inferred.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Assigning a data type, termed *typing*, gives meaning to a sequence of bits such as a value in memory or some object such as a variable.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Associating a sequence of bits with a type conveys that meaning to the programmable hardware to form a *symbolic system* composed of that hardware and some program.
[src:modula-3/type-system] A program associates each value with at least one specific type, but it also can occur that one value is associated with many subtypes.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Other entities, such as objects, modules, communication channels, and dependencies can become associated with a type.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Even a type can become associated with a type.
[src:modula-3/type-system] An implementation of a *type system* could in theory associate identifications called *data type* (a type of a value), *class* (a type of an object), and *kind* (a *type of a type*, or metatype).
[src:modula-3/type-system] These are the abstractions that typing can go through, on a hierarchy of levels contained in a system.
[src:modula-3/type-system] It is challenging to find a sufficiently expressive type system that satisfies all programming practices in a type safe manner.
[src:modula-3/type-system] A programming language compiler can also implement a *dependent type* or an *effect system*, which enables even more program specifications to be verified by a type checker.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Beyond simple value-type pairs, a virtual "region" of code is associated with an "effect" component describing *what* is being done *with what*, and enabling for example to "throw" an error report.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Thus the symbolic system may be a *type and effect system*, which endows it with more safety checking than type checking alone.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Whether automated by the compiler or specified by a programmer, a type system renders program behavior illegal if it falls outside the type-system rules.
[src:modula-3/type-system] A type error occurs when an operation receives a different type of data than it expected.
[src:modula-3/type-system] For example, a type error would happen if a line of code divides two integers, and is passed a string of letters instead of an integer.
[src:modula-3/type-system] It is an unintended condition which might manifest in multiple stages of a program's development.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Thus a facility for detection of the error is needed in the type system.
[src:modula-3/type-system] In some languages, such as Haskell, for which type inference is automated, lint might be available to its compiler to aid in the detection of error.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Type safety contributes to program correctness, but might only guarantee correctness at the cost of making the type checking itself an undecidable problem (as in the halting problem).
[src:modula-3/type-system] In a *type system* with automated type checking, a program may prove to run incorrectly yet produce no compiler errors.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Division by zero is an unsafe and incorrect operation, but a type checker which only runs at compile time does not scan for division by zero in most languages; that division would surface as a runtime error.
[src:modula-3/type-system] To prove the absence of these defects, other kinds of formal methods, collectively known as program analyses, are in common use.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Alternatively, a sufficiently expressive type system, such as in dependently typed languages, can prevent these kinds of errors (for example, expressing *the type of non-zero numbers*).
[src:modula-3/type-system] In addition, software testing is an empirical method for finding errors that such a type checker would not detect.
[src:modula-3/type-system] The process of verifying and enforcing the constraints of types, *type checking*, may occur at compile time (a static check) or at runtime (a dynamic check).
[src:modula-3/type-system] If a language specification requires its typing rules strongly, more or less allowing only those automatic type conversions that do not lose information, one can refer to the process as *strongly typed*; if not, as *weakly typed*.
[src:modula-3/type-system] The terms are not usually used in a strict sense.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Static type checking is the process of verifying the type safety of a program based on analysis of a program's text (source code).
[src:modula-3/type-system] If a program passes a static type checker, then the program is guaranteed to satisfy some set of type safety properties for all possible inputs.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Static type checking can be considered a limited form of program verification (see type safety), and in a type-safe language, can also be considered an optimization.
[src:modula-3/type-system] If a compiler can prove that a program is well-typed, then it does not need to emit dynamic safety checks, allowing the resulting compiled binary to run faster and to be smaller.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Static type checking for Turing-complete languages is inherently conservative.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Even if the expression `<complex test>` always evaluates to `true` at runtime, most type checkers will reject the program as ill-typed, because it is difficult (if not impossible) for a static analyzer to determine that the `else` branch will not be taken.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Consequently, a static type checker will quickly detect type errors in rarely used code paths.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Without static type checking, even code coverage tests with 100% coverage may be unable to find such type errors.
[src:modula-3/type-system] The tests may fail to detect such type errors, because the combination of all places where values are created and all places where a certain value is used must be taken into account.
[src:modula-3/type-system] A number of useful and common programming language features cannot be checked statically, such as downcasting.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Thus, many languages will have both static and dynamic type checking; the static type checker verifies what it can, and dynamic checks verify the rest.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Many languages with static type checking provide a way to bypass the type checker.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Some languages allow programmers to choose between static and dynamic type safety.
[src:modula-3/type-system] For example, historically C# declares variables statically, but C# 4.0 introduces the `dynamic` keyword, which is used to declare variables to be checked dynamically at runtime.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Other languages allow writing code that is not type-safe; for example, in C, programmers can freely cast a value between any two types that have the same size, effectively subverting the type concept.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Dynamic type checking is the process of verifying the type safety of a program at runtime.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Implementations of dynamically type-checked languages generally associate each runtime object with a *type tag* (i.e., a reference to a type) containing its type information.
[src:modula-3/type-system] This runtime type information (RTTI) can also be used to implement dynamic dispatch, late binding, downcasting, reflective programming (reflection), and similar features.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Most type-safe languages include some form of dynamic type checking, even if they also have a static type checker.
[src:modula-3/type-system] The reason for this is that many useful features or properties are difficult or impossible to verify statically.
[src:modula-3/type-system] For example, suppose that a program defines two types, A and B, where B is a subtype of A.
[src:modula-3/type-system] If the program tries to convert a value of type A to type B, which is known as downcasting, then the operation is legal only if the value being converted is actually a value of type B.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Thus, a dynamic check is needed to verify that the operation is safe.
[src:modula-3/type-system] This requirement is one of the criticisms of downcasting.
[src:modula-3/type-system] By definition, dynamic type checking may cause a program to fail at runtime.
[src:modula-3/type-system] In some programming languages, it is possible to anticipate and recover from these failures.
[src:modula-3/type-system] In others, type-checking errors are considered fatal.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Programming languages that include dynamic type checking but not static type checking are often called "dynamically typed programming languages".
[src:modula-3/type-system] Certain languages allow both static and dynamic typing.
[src:modula-3/type-system] For example, Java and some other ostensibly statically typed languages support downcasting types to their subtypes, querying an object to discover its dynamic type and other type operations that depend on runtime type information.
[src:modula-3/type-system] More generally, most programming languages include mechanisms for dispatching over different 'kinds' of data, such as disjoint unions, runtime polymorphism, and variant types.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Even when not interacting with type annotations or type checking, such mechanisms are materially similar to dynamic typing implementations.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Objects in object-oriented languages are usually accessed by a reference whose static target type (or manifest type) is equal to either the object's runtime type (its latent type) or a supertype thereof.
[src:modula-3/type-system] This is conformant with the Liskov substitution principle, which states that all operations performed on an instance of a given type can also be performed on an instance of a subtype.
[src:modula-3/type-system] This concept is also known as subsumption or subtype polymorphism.
[src:modula-3/type-system] In some languages subtypes may also possess covariant or contravariant return types and argument types respectively.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Certain languages, for example Clojure, Common Lisp, or Cython are dynamically type checked by default, but allow programs to opt into static type checking by providing optional annotations.
[src:modula-3/type-system] One reason to use such hints would be to optimize the performance of critical sections of a program.
[src:modula-3/type-system] The programming environment *DrRacket*, a pedagogic environment based on Lisp, and a precursor of the language Racket is also soft-typed.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Conversely, as of version 4.0, the C# language provides a way to indicate that a variable should not be statically type checked.
[src:modula-3/type-system] A variable whose type is `dynamic` will not be subject to static type checking.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Instead, the program relies on runtime type information to determine how the variable may be used.
[src:modula-3/type-system] In Rust, the `dyn std::any::Any` trait object provides dynamic typing of types containing no or only `'static` lifetimes.
[src:modula-3/type-system] The choice between static and dynamic typing requires certain trade-offs.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Static typing can find type errors reliably at compile time, which increases the reliability of the delivered program.
[src:modula-3/type-system] However, programmers disagree over how commonly type errors occur, resulting in further disagreements over the proportion of those bugs that are coded that would be caught by appropriately representing the designed types in code.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Static typing advocates believe programs are more reliable when they have been well type-checked, whereas dynamic-typing advocates point to distributed code that has proven reliable and to small bug databases.
[src:modula-3/type-system] The value of static typing increases as the strength of the type system is increased.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Advocates of dependent typing, implemented in languages such as Dependent ML and Epigram, have suggested that almost all bugs can be considered type errors, if the types used in a program are properly declared by the programmer or correctly inferred by the compiler.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Static typing usually results in compiled code that executes faster.
[src:modula-3/type-system] When the compiler knows the exact data types that are in use (which is necessary for static verification, either through declaration or inference) it can produce optimized machine code.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Some dynamically typed languages such as Common Lisp allow optional type declarations for optimization for this reason.
[src:modula-3/type-system] By contrast, dynamic typing may allow compilers to run faster and interpreters to dynamically load new code, because changes to source code in dynamically typed languages may result in less checking to perform and less code to revisit.
[src:modula-3/type-system] This too may reduce the edit-compile-test-debug cycle.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Statically typed languages that lack type inference (such as C and Java prior to version 10) require that programmers declare the types that a method or function must use.
[src:modula-3/type-system] This can serve as added program documentation, that is active and dynamic, instead of static.
[src:modula-3/type-system] This allows a compiler to prevent it from drifting out of synchrony, and from being ignored by programmers.
[src:modula-3/type-system] However, a language can be statically typed without requiring type declarations (examples include Haskell, Scala, OCaml, F#, Swift, and to a lesser extent C# and C++), so explicit type declaration is not required for static typing in all languages.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Dynamic typing allows constructs that some (simple) static type checking would reject as illegal.
[src:modula-3/type-system] For example, *eval* functions, which execute arbitrary data as code, become possible.
[src:modula-3/type-system] An *eval* function is possible with static typing, but requires advanced uses of algebraic data types.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Further, dynamic typing better accommodates transitional code and prototyping, such as allowing a placeholder data structure (mock object) to be transparently used in place of a full data structure (usually for the purposes of experimentation and testing).
[src:modula-3/type-system] Dynamic typing typically allows duck typing (which enables easier code reuse).
[src:modula-3/type-system] Many languages with static typing also feature duck typing or other mechanisms like generic programming that also enable easier code reuse.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Dynamic typing typically makes metaprogramming easier to use.
[src:modula-3/type-system] For example, C++ templates are typically more cumbersome to write than the equivalent Ruby or Python code since C++ has stronger rules regarding type definitions (for both functions and variables).
[src:modula-3/type-system] This forces a developer to write more boilerplate code for a template than a Python developer would need to.
[src:modula-3/type-system] More advanced runtime constructs such as metaclasses and introspection are often harder to use in statically typed languages.
[src:modula-3/type-system] In some languages, such features may also be used e.g. to generate new types and behaviors on the fly, based on runtime data.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Such advanced constructs are often provided by dynamic programming languages; many of these are dynamically typed, although *dynamic typing* need not be related to *dynamic programming languages*.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Languages are often colloquially referred to as *strongly typed* or *weakly typed*.
[src:modula-3/type-system] In fact, there is no universally accepted definition of what these terms mean.
[src:modula-3/type-system] In general, there are more precise terms to represent the differences between type systems that lead people to call them "strong" or "weak".
[src:modula-3/type-system] A third way of categorizing the type system of a programming language is by the safety of typed operations and conversions.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Computer scientists use the term *type-safe language* to describe languages that do not allow operations or conversions that violate the rules of the type system.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Computer scientists use the term *memory-safe language* (or just *safe language*) to describe languages that do not allow programs to access memory that has not been assigned for their use.
[src:modula-3/type-system] For example, a memory-safe language will check array bounds, or else statically guarantee (i.e., at compile time before execution) that array accesses out of the array boundaries will cause compile-time and perhaps runtime errors.
[src:modula-3/type-system] In this example, the variable `z` will have the value 42.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Although this may not be what the programmer anticipated, it is a well-defined result.
[src:modula-3/type-system] If `y` were a different string, one that could not be converted to a number (e.g., "Hello, World"), the result would be well-defined also.
[src:modula-3/type-system] A program can be type-safe or memory-safe and still crash on an invalid operation.
[src:modula-3/type-system] This is for languages where the type system is not sufficiently advanced to precisely specify the validity of operations on all possible operands.
[src:modula-3/type-system] But if a program encounters an operation that is not type-safe, terminating the program is often the only option.
[src:modula-3/type-system] In this example `z` will point to a memory address five characters beyond `y`, equivalent to three characters after the terminating zero character of the string pointed to by `y`.
[src:modula-3/type-system] This is memory that the program is not expected to access.
[src:modula-3/type-system] In C terms this is simply undefined behaviour and the program may do anything; with a simple compiler it might actually print whatever byte is stored after the string "37".
[src:modula-3/type-system] As this example shows, C is not memory-safe.
[src:modula-3/type-system] As arbitrary data was assumed to be a character, it is also not a type-safe language.
[src:modula-3/type-system] In general, type-safety and memory-safety go hand in hand.
[src:modula-3/type-system] For example, a language that supports pointer arithmetic and number-to-pointer conversions (like C) is neither memory-safe nor type-safe, because it allows arbitrary memory to be accessed as if it were valid memory of any type.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Some languages allow different levels of checking to apply to different regions of code.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Additional tools such as lint and IBM Rational Purify can also be used to achieve a higher level of strictness.
[src:modula-3/type-system] It has been proposed, chiefly by Gilad Bracha, that the choice of type system be made independent of choice of language; that a type system should be a module that can be *plugged* into a language as needed.
[src:modula-3/type-system] He believes this is advantageous, because what he calls mandatory type systems make languages less expressive and code more fragile.
[src:modula-3/type-system] The requirement that the type system does not affect the semantics of the language is difficult to fulfill.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Optional typing is related to, but distinct from, gradual typing.
[src:modula-3/type-system] While both typing disciplines can be used to perform static analysis of code (static typing), optional type systems do not enforce type safety at runtime (dynamic typing).
[src:modula-3/type-system] The term *polymorphism* refers to the ability of code (especially, functions or classes) to act on values of multiple types, or to the ability of different instances of the same data structure to contain elements of different types.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Type systems that allow polymorphism generally do so to improve the potential for code re-use: in a language with polymorphism, programmers need only implement a data structure such as a list or an associative array once, rather than once for each type of element with which they plan to use it.
[src:modula-3/type-system] For this reason computer scientists sometimes call the use of certain forms of polymorphism *generic programming*.
[src:modula-3/type-system] The type-theoretic foundations of polymorphism are closely related to those of abstraction, modularity and (in some cases) subtyping.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Many type systems have been created that are specialized for use in certain environments with certain types of data, or for out-of-band static program analysis.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Frequently, these are based on ideas from formal type theory and are only available as part of prototype research systems.
[src:modula-3/type-system] The following table gives an overview over type theoretic concepts that are used in specialized type systems.
[src:modula-3/type-system] The names M, N, O range over terms and the names $\sigma ,\tau$ range over types.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Also referred to as *dependent sum type*, since ${\textstyle (x:\sigma )\times \tau =\sum _{x:\sigma }\tau }$ .
[src:modula-3/type-system] Dependent types are based on the idea of using scalars or values to more precisely describe the type of some other value.
[src:modula-3/type-system] For example, $\mathrm {matrix} (3,3)$ might be the type of a $3\times 3$ matrix.
[src:modula-3/type-system] where k, m, n are arbitrary positive integer values.
[src:modula-3/type-system] A variant of ML called Dependent ML has been created based on this type system, but because type checking for conventional dependent types is undecidable, not all programs using them can be type-checked without some kind of limits.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Dependent ML limits the sort of equality it can decide to Presburger arithmetic.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Other languages such as Epigram make the value of all expressions in the language decidable so that type checking can be decidable.
[src:modula-3/type-system] However, in general proof of decidability is undecidable, so many programs require hand-written annotations that may be very non-trivial.
[src:modula-3/type-system] As this impedes the development process, many language implementations provide an easy way out in the form of an option to disable this condition.
[src:modula-3/type-system] This, however, comes at the cost of making the type-checker run in an infinite loop when fed programs that do not type-check, causing the compilation to fail.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Linear types, based on the theory of linear logic, and closely related to uniqueness types, are types assigned to values having the property that they have one and only one reference to them at all times.
[src:modula-3/type-system] These are valuable for describing large immutable values such as files, strings, and so on, because any operation that simultaneously destroys a linear object and creates a similar object (such as `str = str + "a"`) can be optimized "under the hood" into an in-place mutation.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Normally this is not possible, as such mutations could cause side effects on parts of the program holding other references to the object, violating referential transparency.
[src:modula-3/type-system] They are also used in the prototype operating system Singularity for interprocess communication, statically ensuring that processes cannot share objects in shared memory to prevent race conditions.
[src:modula-3/type-system] The Clean language (a Haskell-like language) uses this type system to gain a lot of speed (compared to performing a deep copy) while remaining safe.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Intersection types are types describing values that belong to *both* of two other given types with overlapping value sets.
[src:modula-3/type-system] For example, in most implementations of C the signed char has range -128 to 127 and the unsigned char has range 0 to 255, so the intersection type of these two types would have range 0 to 127.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Such an intersection type could be safely passed into functions expecting *either* signed or unsigned chars, because it is compatible with both types.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Such a function could be passed into another function expecting an "`int` → `int`" function safely; it simply would not use the "`float` → `float`" functionality.
[src:modula-3/type-system] In a subclassing hierarchy, the intersection of a type and an ancestor type (such as its parent) is the most derived type.
[src:modula-3/type-system] The intersection of sibling types is empty.
[src:modula-3/type-system] The Forsythe language includes a general implementation of intersection types.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Union types are types describing values that belong to *either* of two types.
[src:modula-3/type-system] For example, in C, the signed char has a -128 to 127 range, and the unsigned char has a 0 to 255 range, so the union of these two types would have an overall "virtual" range of -128 to 255 that may be used partially depending on which union member is accessed.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Any function handling this union type would have to deal with integers in this complete range.
[src:modula-3/type-system] More generally, the only valid operations on a union type are operations that are valid on *both* types being unioned.
[src:modula-3/type-system] C's "union" concept is similar to union types, but is not typesafe, as it permits operations that are valid on *either* type, rather than *both*.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Union types are important in program analysis, where they are used to represent symbolic values whose exact nature (e.g., value or type) is not known.
[src:modula-3/type-system] In a subclassing hierarchy, the union of a type and an ancestor type (such as its parent) is the ancestor type.
[src:modula-3/type-system] The union of sibling types is a subtype of their common ancestor (that is, all operations permitted on their common ancestor are permitted on the union type, but they may also have other valid operations in common).
[src:modula-3/type-system] Existential types are frequently used in connection with record types to represent modules and abstract data types, due to their ability to separate implementation from interface.
[src:modula-3/type-system] For example, the type "T = ∃X { a: X; f: (X → int); }" describes a module interface that has a data member named *a* of type *X* and a function named *f* that takes a parameter of the *same* type *X* and returns an integer.
[src:modula-3/type-system] These types are both subtypes of the more general existential type T and correspond to concrete implementation types, so any value of one of these types is a value of type T.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Given a value "t" of type "T", we know that "t.f(t.a)" is well-typed, regardless of what the abstract type *X* is.
[src:modula-3/type-system] This gives flexibility for choosing types suited to a particular implementation, while clients that use only values of the interface type—the existential type—are isolated from these choices.
[src:modula-3/type-system] In general it's impossible for the typechecker to infer which existential type a given module belongs to.
[src:modula-3/type-system] In the above example intT { a: int; f: (int → int); } could also have the type ∃X { a: X; f: (X → int); }.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Although abstract data types and modules had been implemented in programming languages for quite some time, it wasn't until 1988 that John C.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Mitchell and Gordon Plotkin established the formal theory under the slogan: "Abstract [data] types have existential type".
[src:modula-3/type-system] The theory is a second-order typed lambda calculus similar to System F, but with existential instead of universal quantification.
[src:modula-3/type-system] In a type system with Gradual typing, variables may be assigned a type either at compile-time (which is static typing), or at runtime (which is dynamic typing).
[src:modula-3/type-system] This allows software developers to choose either type paradigm as appropriate, from within a single language.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Gradual typing uses a special type named *dynamic* to represent statically unknown types; gradual typing replaces the notion of type equality with a new relation called *consistency* that relates the dynamic type to every other type.
[src:modula-3/type-system] The consistency relation is symmetric but not transitive.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Many static type systems, such as those of C and Java, require *type declarations*: the programmer must explicitly associate each variable with a specific type.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Others, such as Haskell's, perform *type inference*: the compiler draws conclusions about the types of variables based on how programmers use those variables.
[src:modula-3/type-system] For example, given a function `f(x, y)` that adds `x` and `y` together, the compiler can infer that `x` and `y` must be numbers—since addition is only defined for numbers.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Thus, any call to `f` elsewhere in the program that specifies a non-numeric type (such as a string or list) as an argument would signal an error.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Numerical and string constants and expressions in code can and often do imply type in a particular context.
[src:modula-3/type-system] For example, an expression `3.14` might imply a type of floating-point, while `[1, 2, 3]` might imply a list of integers—typically an array.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Type inference is in general possible, if it is computable in the type system in question.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Moreover, even if inference is not computable in general for a given type system, inference is often possible for a large subset of real-world programs.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Haskell's type system, a version of Hindley–Milner, is a restriction of System Fω to so-called rank-1 polymorphic types, in which type inference is computable.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Most Haskell compilers allow arbitrary-rank polymorphism as an extension, but this makes type inference not computable.
[src:modula-3/type-system] A type system that assigns types to terms in type environments using typing rules is naturally associated with the decision problems of type checking, typability, and type inhabitation.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Some languages like C# or Scala have a unified type system.
[src:modula-3/type-system] This means that all C# types including primitive types inherit from a single root object.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Every type in C# inherits from the Object class.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Some languages, like Java and Raku, have a root type but also have primitive types that are not objects.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Java provides wrapper object types that exist together with the primitive types so developers can use either the wrapper object types or the simpler non-object primitive types.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Raku automatically converts primitive types to objects when their methods are accessed.
[src:modula-3/type-system] A type checker for a statically typed language must verify that the type of any expression is consistent with the type expected by the context in which that expression appears.
[src:modula-3/type-system] For example, in an assignment statement of the form `x := *e*`, the inferred type of the expression *`e`* must be consistent with the declared or inferred type of the variable `x`.
[src:modula-3/type-system] This notion of consistency, called *compatibility*, is specific to each programming language.
[src:modula-3/type-system] If the type of *`e`* and the type of `x` are the same, and assignment is allowed for that type, then this is a valid expression.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Thus, in the simplest type systems, the question of whether two types are compatible reduces to that of whether they are *equal* (or *equivalent*).
[src:modula-3/type-system] Different languages, however, have different criteria for when two type expressions are understood to denote the same type.
[src:modula-3/type-system] In languages with subtyping, the compatibility relation is more complex: If `B` is a subtype of `A`, then a value of type `B` can be used in a context where one of type `A` is expected (covariant), even if the reverse is not true.
[src:modula-3/type-system] Like equivalence, the subtype relation is defined differently for each programming language, with many variations possible.
[src:modula-3/type-system] The presence of parametric or ad hoc polymorphism in a language may also have implications for type compatibility.
